# nl-rag distilled facts ‚Äî domain: molecular-genetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gel is easy to cast, has relatively fewer charged groups, and is particularly suitable for separating DNA of size range most often encountered in laboratories, which accounts for the popularity of its use.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The separated DNA may be viewed with stain, most commonly under UV light, and the DNA fragments can be extracted from the gel with relative ease.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Most agarose gels used are between 0.7‚Äì2% dissolved in a suitable electrophoresis buffer.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gel is a three-dimensional matrix formed of helical agarose molecules in supercoiled bundles that are aggregated into three-dimensional structures with channels and pores through which biomolecules can pass.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The 3-D structure is held together with hydrogen bonds and can therefore be disrupted by heating back to a liquid state.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The melting temperature is different from the gelling temperature, depending on the sources, agarose gel has a gelling temperature of 35‚Äì42 ¬∞C (95‚Äì108 ¬∞F) and a melting temperature of 85‚Äì95 ¬∞C (185‚Äì203 ¬∞F).
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Low-melting and low-gelling agaroses made through chemical modifications are also available.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gel has large pore size and good gel strength, making it suitable as an anticonvection medium for the electrophoresis of DNA and large protein molecules.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The pore size of a 1% gel has been estimated from 100 nm to 200‚Äì500 nm, and its gel strength allows gels as dilute as 0.15% to form a slab for gel electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Low-concentration gels (0.1‚Äì0.2%) however are fragile and therefore hard to handle.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gel has lower resolving power than polyacrylamide gel for DNA but has a greater range of separation, and is therefore used for DNA fragments of usually 50‚Äì20,000 bp in size.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The limit of resolution for standard agarose gel electrophoresis is around 750 kb, but resolution of over 6 Mb is possible with pulsed field gel electrophoresis (PFGE).
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] It can also be used to separate large proteins, and it is the preferred matrix for the gel electrophoresis of particles with effective radii larger than 5‚Äì10 nm.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] A 0.9% agarose gel has pores large enough for the entry of bacteriophage T4.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The agarose polymer contains charged groups, in particular pyruvate and sulfate.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] These negatively charged groups create a flow of water in the opposite direction to the movement of DNA in a process called electroendosmosis (EEO), and can therefore slow the movement of DNA and cause blurring of bands.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Higher concentration gels would have higher electroendosmotic flow.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Low EEO agarose is therefore generally preferred for use in agarose gel electrophoresis of nucleic acids, but high EEO agarose may be used for other purposes.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The lower sulfate content of low EEO agarose, particularly low-melting point (LMP) agarose, is also beneficial in cases where the DNA extracted from gel is to be used for further manipulation as the presence of contaminating sulfates may affect some subsequent procedures, such as ligation and PCR.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Zero EEO agaroses however are undesirable for some applications as they may be made by adding positively charged groups and such groups can affect subsequent enzyme reactions.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Electroendosmosis is a reason agarose is used in preference to agar as the agaropectin component in agar contains a significant amount of negatively charged sulfate and carboxyl groups.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The removal of agaropectin in agarose substantially reduces the EEO, as well as reducing the non-specific adsorption of biomolecules to the gel matrix.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] However, for some applications such as the electrophoresis of serum proteins, a high EEO may be desirable, and agaropectin may be added in the gel used.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Smaller molecules travel faster than larger molecules in gel, and double-stranded DNA moves at a rate that is inversely proportional to the logarithm of the number of base pairs.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] For standard agarose gel electrophoresis, larger molecules are resolved better using a low concentration gel while smaller molecules separate better at high concentration gel.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Higher concentration gels, however, require longer run times (sometimes days).
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The movement of the DNA may be affected by the conformation of the DNA molecule, for example, supercoiled DNA usually moves faster than relaxed DNA because it is tightly coiled and hence more compact.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] In a normal plasmid DNA preparation, multiple forms of DNA may be present.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Gel electrophoresis of the plasmids would normally show the negatively supercoiled form as the main band, while nicked DNA (open circular form) and the relaxed closed circular form appears as minor bands.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The rate at which the various forms move however can change using different electrophoresis conditions, and the mobility of larger circular DNA may be more strongly affected than linear DNA by the pore size of the gel.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Ethidium bromide which intercalates into circular DNA can change the charge, length, as well as the superhelicity of the DNA molecule, therefore its presence in gel during electrophoresis can affect its movement.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] For example, the positive charge of ethidium bromide can reduce the DNA movement by 15%.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gel electrophoresis can be used to resolve circular DNA with different supercoiling topology.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] DNA damage due to increased cross-linking will also reduce electrophoretic DNA migration in a dose-dependent way.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The rate of migration of the DNA is proportional to the voltage applied, i.e. the higher the voltage, the faster the DNA moves.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The resolution of large DNA fragments however is lower at high voltage.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The mobility of DNA may also change in an unsteady field ‚Äì in a field that is periodically reversed, the mobility of DNA of a particular size may drop significantly at a particular cycling frequency.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] This phenomenon can result in band inversion in field inversion gel electrophoresis (FIGE), whereby larger DNA fragments move faster than smaller ones.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The negative charge of its phosphate backbone moves the DNA towards the positively charged anode during electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] However, the migration of DNA molecules in solution, in the absence of a gel matrix, is independent of molecular weight during electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The gel matrix is therefore responsible for the separation of DNA by size during electrophoresis, and a number of models exist to explain the mechanism of separation of biomolecules in gel matrix.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] A widely accepted one is the Ogston model which treats the polymer matrix as a sieve.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] A globular protein or a random coil DNA moves through the interconnected pores, and the movement of larger molecules is more likely to be impeded and slowed down by collisions with the gel matrix, and the molecules of different sizes can therefore be separated in this sieving process.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The Ogston model however breaks down for large molecules whereby the pores are significantly smaller than size of the molecule.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] For DNA molecules of size greater than 1 kb, a reptation model (or its variants) is most commonly used.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] This model assumes that the DNA can crawl in a "snake-like" fashion (hence "reptation") through the pores as an elongated molecule.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] A biased reptation model applies at higher electric field strength, whereby the leading end of the molecule become strongly biased in the forward direction and pulls the rest of the molecule along.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The details of an agarose gel electrophoresis experiment may vary depending on methods, but most follow a general procedure.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The gel is prepared by dissolving the agarose powder in an appropriate buffer, such as TAE or TBE, to be used in electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The agarose is dispersed in the buffer before heating it to near-boiling point, but avoid boiling.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The melted agarose is allowed to cool sufficiently before pouring the solution into a cast as the cast may warp or crack if the agarose solution is too hot.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] A comb is placed in the cast to create wells for loading sample, and the gel should be completely set before use.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The concentration of gel affects the resolution of DNA separation.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The agarose gel is composed of microscopic pores through which the molecules travel, and there is an inverse relationship between the pore size of the agarose gel and the concentration ‚Äì pore size decreases as the density of agarose fibers increases.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] High gel concentration improves separation of smaller DNA molecules, while lowering gel concentration permits large DNA molecules to be separated.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The process allows fragments ranging from 50 base pairs to several mega bases to be separated depending on the gel concentration used.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The concentration is measured in weight of agarose over volume of buffer used (g/ml).
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] For a standard agarose gel electrophoresis, a 0.8% gel gives good separation or resolution of large 5‚Äì10kb DNA fragments, while 2% gel gives good resolution for small 0.2‚Äì1kb fragments.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] 1% gels is often used for a standard electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] High percentage gels are often brittle and may not set evenly, while low percentage gels (0.1-0.2%) are fragile and not easy to handle.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Low-melting-point (LMP) agarose gels are also more fragile than normal agarose gel.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Low-melting point agarose may be used on its own or simultaneously with standard agarose for the separation and isolation of DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] PFGE and FIGE are often done with high percentage agarose gels.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Once the gel has set, the comb is removed, leaving wells where DNA samples can be loaded.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Loading buffer is mixed with the DNA sample before the mixture is loaded into the wells.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The loading buffer contains a dense compound, which may be glycerol, sucrose, or Ficoll, that raises the density of the sample so that the DNA sample may sink to the bottom of the well.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] If the DNA sample contains residual ethanol after its preparation, it may float out of the well.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The loading buffer also includes colored dyes such as xylene cyanol and bromophenol blue used to monitor the progress of the electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The DNA samples are loaded using a pipette.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gel electrophoresis is most commonly done horizontally in a subaquaeous mode whereby the slab gel is completely submerged in buffer during electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] It is also possible, but less common, to perform the electrophoresis vertically, as well as horizontally with the gel raised on agarose legs using an appropriate apparatus.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The buffer used in the gel is the same as the running buffer in the electrophoresis tank, which is why electrophoresis in the subaquaeous mode is possible with agarose gel.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] For optimal resolution of DNA greater than 2 kb in size in standard gel electrophoresis, 5 to 8 V/cm is recommended (the distance in cm refers to the distance between electrodes, therefore this recommended voltage would be 5 to 8 multiplied by the distance between the electrodes in cm).
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Voltage may also be limited by the fact that it heats the gel and may cause the gel to melt if it is run at high voltage for a prolonged period, especially if the gel used is LMP agarose gel.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Too high a voltage may also reduce resolution, as well as causing band streaking for large DNA molecules.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Too low a voltage may lead to broadening of band for small DNA fragments due to dispersion and diffusion.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Since DNA is not visible in natural light, the progress of the electrophoresis is monitored using colored dyes.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Xylene cyanol (light blue color) comigrates large DNA fragments, while Bromophenol blue (dark blue) comigrates with the smaller fragments.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Less commonly used dyes include Cresol Red and Orange G which migrate ahead of bromophenol blue.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] A DNA marker is also run together for the estimation of the molecular weight of the DNA fragments.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Note however that the size of a circular DNA like plasmids cannot be accurately gauged using standard markers unless it has been linearized by restriction digest, alternatively a supercoiled DNA marker may be used.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] DNA as well as RNA are normally visualized by staining with ethidium bromide, which intercalates into the major grooves of the DNA and fluoresces under UV light.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The intercalation depends on the concentration of DNA and thus, a band with high intensity will indicate a higher amount of DNA compared to a band of less intensity.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The ethidium bromide may be added to the agarose solution before it gels, or the DNA gel may be stained later after electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Destaining of the gel is not necessary but may produce better images.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Other methods of staining are available; examples are MIDORI Green, SYBR Green, GelRed, methylene blue, brilliant cresyl blue, Nile blue sulfate, and crystal violet.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] SYBR Green, GelRed and other similar commercial products are sold as safer alternatives to ethidium bromide as it has been shown to be mutagenic in Ames test, although the carcinogenicity of ethidium bromide has not actually been established.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] SYBR Green requires the use of a blue-light transilluminator.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] DNA stained with crystal violet can be viewed under natural light without the use of a UV transilluminator which is an advantage, however it may not produce a strong band.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] When stained with ethidium bromide, the gel is viewed with an ultraviolet (UV) transilluminator.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The UV light excites the electrons within the aromatic ring of ethidium bromide, and once they return to the ground state, light is released, making the DNA and ethidium bromide complex fluoresce.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Standard transilluminators use wavelengths of 302/312-nm (UV-B), however exposure of DNA to UV radiation for as little as 45 seconds can produce damage to DNA and affect subsequent procedures, for example reducing the efficiency of transformation, *in vitro* transcription, and PCR.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Exposure of DNA to UV radiation therefore should be limited.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Using a higher wavelength of 365 nm (UV-A range) causes less damage to the DNA but also produces much weaker fluorescence with ethidium bromide.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Where multiple wavelengths can be selected in the transilluminator, shorter wavelength can be used to capture images, while longer wavelength should be used if it is necessary to work on the gel for any extended period of time.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The transilluminator apparatus may also contain image capture devices, such as a digital or polaroid camera, that allow an image of the gel to be taken or printed.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] For gel electrophoresis of protein, the bands may be visualised with Coomassie or silver stains.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The separated DNA bands are often used for further procedures, and a DNA band may be cut out of the gel as a slice, dissolved and purified.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Contaminants however may affect some downstream procedures such as PCR, and low melting point agarose may be preferred in some cases as it contains fewer of the sulfates that can affect some enzymatic reactions.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The gels may also be used for blotting techniques.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] In general, the ideal buffer should have good conductivity, produce less heat and have a long life.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] There are a number of buffers used for agarose electrophoresis; common ones for nucleic acids include tris/acetate/EDTA (TAE) and tris/borate/EDTA (TBE).
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The buffers used contain EDTA to inactivate many nucleases which require divalent cation for their function.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] The borate in TBE buffer can be problematic as borate can polymerize, and/or interact with cis diols such as those found in RNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] TAE has the lowest buffering capacity, but it provides the best resolution for larger DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] This means a lower voltage and more time, but a better product.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Many other buffers have been proposed, e.g. lithium borate (LB), iso electric histidine, pK matched goods buffers, etc.; in most cases the purported rationale is lower current (less heat) and or matched ion mobilities, which leads to longer buffer life.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Tris-phosphate buffer has high buffering capacity but cannot be used if DNA extracted is to be used in phosphate sensitive reaction.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] LB is relatively new and is ineffective in resolving fragments larger than 5 kbp; However, with its low conductivity, a much higher voltage could be used (up to 35 V/cm), which means a shorter analysis time for routine electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] As low as one base pair size difference could be resolved in 3% agarose gel with an extremely low conductivity medium (1 mM lithium borate).
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Other buffering system may be used in specific applications, for example, barbituric acid-sodium barbiturate or tris-barbiturate buffers may be used for in agarose gel electrophoresis of proteins, for example in the detection of abnormal distribution of proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Agarose gels are easily cast and handled compared to other matrices and nucleic acids are not chemically altered during electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] After the experiment is finished, the resulting gel can be stored in a plastic bag in a refrigerator.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Electrophoresis is performed in buffer solutions to reduce pH changes due to the electric field, which is important because the charge of DNA and RNA depends on pH, but running for too long can exhaust the buffering capacity of the solution.
[src:molecular-genetics/agarose-gel-electrophoresis] Further, different preparations of genetic material may not migrate consistently with each other, for morphological or other reasons.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel isolated and described the five organic compounds that are present in nucleic acid: adenine, cytosine, guanine, thymine, and uracil.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] These compounds were later shown to be nucleobases, and are key in the formation of DNA and RNA, the genetic material found in all living cells.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel was an important influence on and collaborator with other important researchers in biochemistry, including Henry Drysdale Dakin, Friedrich Miescher, Edwin B.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Hart, and his professor and mentor, Felix Hoppe-Seyler.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel was editor of the Zeitschrift f√ºr Physiologische Chemie (Journal of Physiological Chemistry) from 1895 until his death.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel also conducted important research into the composition of protein, and his research predicted the discovery of the polypeptide nature of the protein molecule.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] The Albrecht Kossel Institute for Neuroregeneration at the University of Rostock is named in his honor.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel was born in Rostock, Germany as the son of the merchant and Prussian consul Albrecht Karl Ludwig Enoch Kossel and his wife Clara Jeppe Kossel.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] As a youth, Kossel attended the Gymnasium at Rostock, where he evidenced substantial interest in chemistry and botany.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1872, Kossel attended the University of Strassburg to study medicine.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He studied under Felix Hoppe-Seyler, who was head of the department of biochemistry, the only such institution in Germany at the time.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He attended lectures by Anton de Bary, Waldeyer, August Kundt, and Baeyer.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He completed his studies at University of Rostock, and passed his German medical license exam in 1877.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] After completing his university studies, Kossel returned to the University of Strassburg as research assistant to Felix Hoppe-Seyler.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] At the time, Hoppe-Seyler was intensely interested in research concerning an acidic substance that had first been chemically isolated from pus cells by one of his former students, Friedrich Miescher, in 1869.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Unlike protein, the substance contained considerable amounts of phosphorus, but with its high acidity, it was unlike any cellular substance that had yet been observed.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel showed that the substance, called "nuclein", consisted of a protein component and a non-protein component.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel further isolated and described the non-protein component.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] This substance has become known as *nucleic acid*, which contains the genetic information found in all living cells.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1883, Kossel left Strassburg to become Director of the Chemistry Division of the Physiological Institute at the University of Berlin.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In this post, he succeeded Eugen Baumann and worked under the supervision of Emil du Bois-Reymond.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel continued his previous work on the nucleic acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] During the period 1885 to 1901, he was able to isolate and name its five constituent organic compounds: adenine, cytosine, guanine, thymine, and uracil.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] These compounds are now known collectively as nucleobases, and they provide the molecular structure necessary in the formation of stable DNA and RNA molecules.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1895, Kossel was professor of physiology as well as director of the Physiological Institute at the University of Marburg.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Around this time, he began investigations into the chemical composition of proteins, the alterations in proteins during transformation into peptone, the peptide components of cells, and other investigations.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1896, Kossel discovered histidine, then worked out the classical method for the quantitative separation of the "hexone bases" (the alpha-amino acids arginine, histidine, agmatine and lysine).
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He was also the first to isolate theophylline, a therapeutic drug found naturally in tea and cocoa beans.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1901, Kossel was named to a similar post at Heidelberg University, and became director of the Heidelberg Institute for Protein Investigation.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] His research predicted the discovery of the polypeptide nature of the protein molecule.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1910 for his research in cell biology, the chemical composition of the cell nucleus, and for his work in isolating and describing nucleic acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] The award was presented on 10 December 1910.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In the autumn of 1911, Kossel was invited to the United States to deliver the Herter Lecture at Johns Hopkins.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Traveling with his wife Luise and daughter Gertrude, he took the opportunity to travel and to visit acquaintances, one of which was Eugene W.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Hilgard, professor emeritus of agricultural chemistry at the University of California at Berkeley, who was also his wife's cousin.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He also visited and delivered lectures at several other universities, including the University of Chicago.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] On the occasion of his visit to New York City, Kossel was interviewed by a reporter from *The New York Times*.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel's English was reportedly very good, and his self-effacing modesty is voluminously mentioned in the reporter's account.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] His Herter lecture at Johns Hopkins was titled, "The Proteins".
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] This was the only time Kossel ever visited the United States.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] With his distinguished English pupil Henry Drysdale Dakin, Kossel investigated arginase, the ferment which hydrolyses arginine into urea and ornithine.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Later, he discovered agmatine in herring roe and devised a method for preparing it.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Another of Kossel's students was American biochemist Edwin B.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Hart, who would later return to the United States to participate in the "Single-grain experiment" (1907‚Äì1911) and be part of research teams that would determine the nutritive causes of anemia and goiter.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Another was Otto Folin, an American chemist who discovered Phosphocreatine.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1923, Kossel was honored by being named Germany's representative to the Eleventh Physiological Congress in Edinburgh, Scotland.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] When he appeared before the assembled scientists, they gave him an ovation that lasted several minutes.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] At the congress, he was conferred an honorary degree by the University of Edinburgh.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1924, Kossel became professor emeritus, but continued to lecture at Heidelberg University.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In April 1927, he attended the Lister Centenary Celebration held in England.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] During the last years of Kossel's life, he conducted important research into the composition of the protein types protamines and histones, and introduced flavianic acid for the quantitative separation of arginine, histidine and lysine in proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] A monograph describing this work was published shortly after his death.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel contributed to early issues of the Zeitschrift f√ºr Physiologische Chemie (Journal of Physiological Chemistry).
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] This publication was founded by his professor and mentor, Felix Hoppe-Seyler, in 1877, the same year that Kossel started work as his research assistant.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] After Hoppe-Seyler's death in 1895, Kossel took over editorship of the Zeitschrift and continued in that role until his own death in 1927.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1886, Kossel married Luise Holtzman, daughter of Adolf Holtzmann.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Holtzmann was Professor at the University of Heidelberg, lecturing in German literature as well as Sanskrit.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He was also a noted philologist of his day.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] The couple had three children, two of whom survived to maturity: Walther, born in 1888, and daughter Gertrude, born in 1889.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Son Walther Kossel (1888‚Äì1956) became a prominent physicist and was professor of theoretical physics and director of the Physics Institute at the University of T√ºbingen.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He is known for his theory of the chemical bond (ionic bond/octet rule), the Sommerfeld‚ÄìKossel displacement law, and other achievements.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Albrecht Kossel was apparently not greatly interested in politics, but in 1914 he did not sign the propaganda Pronunciamento of German professors at the start of the war.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] He suffered under the lies which filled the world in war time.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In 1917 Kossel was summoned by the government to pronounce that the allotted food provisions were sufficient.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Through his marriage to Luise, Kossel was related to several prominent Americans, including soil science pioneer Eugene W.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Hilgard, journalist and financier Henry Villard, and abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Luise Kossel died in 1913 of acute pancreatitis.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Kossel died quietly on 5 July 1927, after a recurring attack of angina pectoris.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] Albrecht Kossel is considered one of the great scientists of biochemistry and genetics.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] By isolating and defining nucleic acid and the nucleobases, he provided the necessary precursors that led to the double-helix model of DNA, diffraction photographed by Rosalind Franklin, further devised by James D.
[src:molecular-genetics/albrecht-kossel] In the Nobel Prize introduction speech, his elucidation of the chemical nature of components of nucleic acids and chromatin was highlighted as a major contribution to biochemistry.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] An **allele** is a variant of the sequence of nucleotides at a particular location, or locus, on a DNA molecule.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Alleles can differ at a single position through single-nucleotide polymorphisms, but they can also have insertions and deletions of up to several thousand base pairs.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Most alleles result in little or no change in the characteristics of an individual organism but sometimes different alleles can result in different observable phenotypic traits such as antibiotic resistance in bacteria, developmental mutations in fruit flies, and genetic diseases in humans.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Nearly all multicellular organisms have two sets of chromosomes at some point in their biological life cycle; that is, they are diploid.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] For a given locus, if the two chromosomes contain the same allele, they, and the organism, are homozygous with respect to that allele.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] If the alleles are different, they, and the organism, are heterozygous with respect to those alleles.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] A notable example of this is Gregor Mendel's discovery that the white and purple flower colors in pea plants were the result of a single gene with two alleles.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Mendel's discovery of what are now known as alleles resulted in three laws that help understand how alleles are passed on to progeny.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Popular definitions of 'allele' typically refer only to different alleles within genes.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] For example, the ABO blood grouping is controlled by the ABO gene, which has six common alleles (variants).
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] In population genetics, nearly every living human's phenotype for the ABO gene is some combination of just these six alleles.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] It derives from the Greek prefix ·ºÄŒªŒªŒ∑ŒªŒø-, *allelo-*, meaning "mutual", "reciprocal", or "each other", which itself is related to the Greek adjective ·ºÑŒªŒªŒøœÇ, *allos* (cognate with Latin *alius*), meaning "other".
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] In many cases, genotypic interactions between the two alleles at a locus can be described as dominant or recessive, according to which of the two homozygous phenotypes the heterozygote most resembles.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Where the heterozygote is indistinguishable from one of the homozygotes, the allele expressed is the one that leads to the "dominant" phenotype, and the other allele is said to be "recessive".
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] In the case of a heterozygote, the dominant allele will mask the effect of the recessive allele, giving a dominant phenotype.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] The phenotype of recessive alleles are observable when an organism is homozygous recessive for a gene.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] The degree and pattern of dominance varies among loci.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] This type of interaction was first formally-described by Gregor Mendel.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] However, many traits defy this simple categorization and the phenotypes are modelled by co-dominance and polygenic inheritance.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] The term "wild type" allele is sometimes used to describe an allele that is thought to contribute to the typical phenotypic character as seen in "wild" populations of organisms, such as fruit flies (*Drosophila melanogaster*).
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Such a "wild type" allele was historically regarded as leading to a dominant (overpowering ‚Äì always expressed), common, and normal phenotype, in contrast to "mutant" alleles that lead to recessive, rare, and frequently deleterious phenotypes.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] It is now appreciated that most or all gene loci are highly polymorphic, with multiple alleles, whose frequencies vary from population to population, and that a great deal of genetic variation is hidden in the form of alleles that do not produce obvious phenotypic differences.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Wild type alleles are often denoted by a superscript plus sign (*i.e.*, *p+* for an allele *p*).
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] A population or species of organisms typically includes multiple alleles at each locus among various individuals.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Allelic variation at a locus is measurable as the number of alleles (polymorphism) present, or the proportion of heterozygotes in the population.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] A null allele is a gene variant that lacks the gene's normal function because it either is not expressed, or the expressed protein is inactive.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] For example, at the gene locus for the ABO blood type carbohydrate antigens in humans, classical genetics recognizes three alleles, IA, IB, and i, which determine compatibility of blood transfusions.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] (It is now known that each of the A, B, and O alleles is actually a class of multiple alleles with different DNA sequences that produce proteins with identical properties: more than 70 alleles are known at the ABO locus.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] The frequency of alleles in a diploid population can be used to predict the frequencies of the corresponding genotypes (see Hardy‚ÄìWeinberg principle).
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] where *p* is the frequency of one allele and *q* is the frequency of the alternative allele, which necessarily sum to unity.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Then, *p*2 is the fraction of the population homozygous for the first allele, 2*pq* is the fraction of heterozygotes, and *q*2 is the fraction homozygous for the alternative allele.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] If the first allele is dominant to the second then the fraction of the population that will show the dominant phenotype is *p*2 + 2*pq*, and the fraction with the recessive phenotype is *q*2.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] A number of genetic disorders are caused when an individual inherits two recessive alleles for a single-gene trait.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Recessive genetic disorders include albinism, cystic fibrosis, galactosemia, phenylketonuria (PKU), and Tay‚ÄìSachs disease.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Other disorders are also due to recessive alleles, but because the gene locus is located on the X chromosome, so that males have only one copy (that is, they are hemizygous), they are more frequent in males than in females.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Examples include red‚Äìgreen color blindness and fragile X syndrome.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] Other disorders, such as Huntington's disease, occur when an individual inherits only one dominant allele.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] While heritable traits are typically studied in terms of genetic alleles, epigenetic marks such as DNA methylation can be inherited at specific genomic regions in certain species, a process termed transgenerational epigenetic inheritance.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] The term *epiallele* is used to distinguish these heritable marks from traditional alleles, which are defined by nucleotide sequence.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] A specific class of epiallele, the metastable epialleles, has been discovered in mice and in humans which is characterized by stochastic (probabilistic) establishment of epigenetic state that can be mitotically inherited.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] The term "idiomorph", from Greek 'morphos' (form) and 'idio' (singular, unique), was introduced in 1990 in place of "allele" to denote sequences at the same locus in different strains that have no sequence similarity and probably do not share a common phylogenetic relationship.
[src:molecular-genetics/allele] It is used mainly in the genetic research of mycology.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (Œ±-), beta- (Œ≤-), gamma- (Œ≥-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3‚àíCH(NH2)‚àíCOOH.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminos√§ure*, was used earlier.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or Œ±-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3‚àíCXY‚àíCXY‚àíCO‚àí2, such as Œ≤-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are Œ≤-amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3‚àíCXY‚àíCXY‚àíCXY‚àíCO‚àí2 are Œ≥-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the Œ±‚Äìcarbon.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the Œ±‚Äìcarbon is stereogenic.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Br√∏nsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Br√∏nsted acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the Œ±-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the Œ≤-carbon.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein‚Äìprotein interactions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with ‚àíNH+3 (‚àíNH+2‚àí in the case of proline) and ‚àíCO‚àí2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus Œ±-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO‚àí2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3‚àíCHR‚àíCO‚àí2, and the so-called "neutral forms" ‚àíNH2‚àíCHR‚àíCO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3‚àíCHR‚àíCO2H.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2‚àíCHR‚àíCO‚àí2.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Br√∏nsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Br√∏nsted bases in proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Br√∏nsted acid.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Br√∏nsted acid and a base.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ‚ÅÝ1/2‚ÅÝ(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form ‚àíNH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ‚ÅÝ1/2‚ÅÝ(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC‚ÄìIUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz‚ÄìPhe‚ÄìboroLeu, and MG132 is Z‚ÄìLeu‚ÄìLeu‚ÄìLeu‚Äìal.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids ‚Äì for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of Œ±-amino acids in biology is the Œ≤-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Codon‚Äìamino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal‚Äìamino acid chelates.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to Œ±-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:molecular-genetics/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a serious result of AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistance arises through spontaneous mutation, horizontal gene transfer, and increased selective pressure from antibiotic overuse, both in medicine and agriculture, which accelerates resistance development.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Preventive measures, such as using narrow-spectrum antibiotics and improving hygiene practices, aim to reduce the spread of resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) claims that AMR is one of the top global public health and development threats, estimating that bacterial AMR was directly responsible for 1.27 million global deaths in 2019 and contributed to 4.95 million deaths.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The burden of AMR is immense, with nearly 5 million annual deaths associated with resistant infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Infections from AMR microbes are more challenging to treat and often require costly alternative therapies that may have more severe side effects.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Moreover, the WHO and other international bodies warn that AMR could lead to up to 10 million deaths annually by 2050 unless actions are taken.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Global initiatives, such as calls for international AMR treaties, emphasize coordinated efforts to limit misuse, fund research, and provide access to necessary antimicrobials in developing nations.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, the COVID-19 pandemic redirected resources and scientific attention away from AMR, intensifying the challenge.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance means that a microorganism is resistant to an antimicrobial drug that was once able to treat an infection by that microorganism.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistance is a property of the microbe, not a person or other organism infected by a microbe.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] All types of microbes can develop drug resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Thus, there are antibiotic, antifungal, antiviral and antiparasitic resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a subset of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This more specific resistance is linked to bacteria and thus broken down into two further subsets, microbiological and clinical.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbiological resistance is the most common and occurs from genes, mutated or inherited, that allow the bacteria to resist the mechanism to kill the microbe associated with certain antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Clinical resistance is shown through the failure of many therapeutic techniques where the bacteria that are normally susceptible to a treatment become resistant after surviving the outcome of the treatment.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In both cases of acquired resistance, the bacteria can pass the genetic catalyst for resistance through horizontal gene transfer: conjugation, transduction, or transformation.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This allows the resistance to spread across the same species of pathogen or even similar bacterial pathogens.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] WHO report released April 2014 stated, "this serious threat is no longer a prediction for the future, it is happening right now in every region of the world and has the potential to affect anyone, of any age, in any country.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2024, nearly 5 million deaths were associated with AMR and deaths attributable to AMR numbered 1.27 million.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One in five people who died due to AMR were children under five years old.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2018, WHO considered antibiotic resistance to be one of the biggest threats to global health, food security and development.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control calculated that in 2015 there were 671,689 infections in the EU and European Economic Area caused by antibiotic-resistant bacteria, resulting in 33,110 deaths.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Most were acquired in healthcare settings.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2019 there were 133,000 deaths caused by AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] AMR is driven largely by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] They reproduce and spread quickly, and they also can adapt to their environment and change how well they can survive.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Yet, at the same time, many people do not have access to essential antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This leads to microbes either evolving a defense against drugs used to treat them, or certain strains of microbes that have a natural resistance to antimicrobials becoming much more prevalent than the ones that are easily defeated with medication.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Genetic changes can also occur, which would allow the microbe to survive.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While antimicrobial resistance does occur naturally over time, the use of antimicrobial agents in a variety of settings both within the healthcare industry and outside of has led to antimicrobial resistance becoming increasingly more prevalent.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Although many microbes develop resistance to antibiotics over time through natural mutation, overprescribing and inappropriate prescription of antibiotics have accelerated the problem.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] During mutation, when replication happens, these mutations help individual microbes survive exposure.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] (NIAID, 2025) It is possible that as many as 1 in 3 prescriptions written for antibiotics are unnecessary.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Every year, approximately 154 million prescriptions for antibiotics are written.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Of these, up to 46 million are unnecessary or inappropriate for the condition that the patient has.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbes may naturally develop resistance through genetic mutations that occur during cell division, and although random mutations are rare, many microbes reproduce frequently and rapidly, increasing the chances of members of the population acquiring a mutation that increases resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In contrast to that, recent research suggests that, contrary to the traditional model of rapid genetic mutation, mycobacteria maintain high genomic stability under antibiotic pressure, relying instead on phenotypic tolerance and DNA-repair mechanisms for survival.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Many individuals stop taking antibiotics when they begin to feel better.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] When this occurs, it is possible that the microbes that are less susceptible to treatment still remain in the body.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] If these microbes are able to continue to reproduce, this can lead to an infection by bacteria that are less susceptible or even resistant to an antibiotic.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbes may also get genes from each other, which makes them drug-resistant.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Bacteria that have drug-resistant DNA often transfer a copy of these genes to the other bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This process, known as horizontal gene transfer, allows resistance genes to spread rapidly between different bacterial species through mechanisms such as conjugation, transformation, and transduction.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Bacteria become resistant to antibiotics by changing themselves or acquiring resistance genes from other bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Over the past 20 years, antimicrobial resistance (AMR) has grown, making common infections like respiratory infections, urinary tract infections, STDs, and tuberculosis harder to treat.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] New antibiotics are not being developed fast enough and may lead to a "post-antibiotic era" where some infections are untreatable.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] AMR makes infections more difficult and costly to treat.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Proper antibiotic use‚Äîcorrect drug, dose, and duration‚Äîand strict hospital hygiene are essential.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Combating AMR requires cooperation among governments, healthcare workers, researchers, pharmaceutical companies, farmers, and the public through responsible antibiotic use, monitoring resistance, limiting antibiotics in animals, and improving access to medicines, vaccines, and tests.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Prevention is the most effective strategy.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Along with careful antibiotic use, there is a need for new drugs, alternative treatments, better diagnostics, and vaccines.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Without coordinated global action, vital medical procedures like surgery, organ transplants, neonatal care, and cancer treatment could be at risk.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can evolve naturally due to continued exposure to antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Natural selection means that organisms that are able to adapt to their environment, survive, and continue to produce offspring.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] As a result, the types of microorganisms that are able to survive over time with continued attack by certain antimicrobial agents will naturally become more prevalent in the environment, and those without this resistance will become obsolete.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Some contemporary antimicrobial resistances have also evolved naturally before the use of antimicrobials of human clinical uses.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For instance, methicillin-resistance evolved as a pathogen of hedgehogs, possibly as a co-evolutionary adaptation of the pathogen to hedgehogs that are infected by a dermatophyte that naturally produces antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Also, many soil fungi and bacteria are natural competitors and the original antibiotic penicillin discovered by Alexander Fleming rapidly lost clinical effectiveness in treating humans and, furthermore, none of the other natural penicillins (F, K, N, X, O, U1 or U6) are currently in clinical use.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can be acquired from other microbes through swapping genes in a process termed horizontal gene transfer.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This means that once a gene for resistance to an antibiotic appears in a microbial community, it can then spread to other microbes, potentially moving from a non-disease causing microbe to a disease-causing microbe.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This process is heavily driven by the natural selection processes that happen during antibiotic use or misuse.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Over time, most of the strains of bacteria and infections present will be the type resistant to the antimicrobial agent being used to treat them, making this agent now ineffective to defeat most microbes.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] With the increased use of antimicrobial agents, there is a speeding up of this natural process.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In the vast majority of countries, antibiotics can only be prescribed by a doctor and supplied by a pharmacy.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication by consumers is defined as "the taking of medicines on one's own initiative or on another person's suggestion, who is not a certified medical professional", and it has been identified as one of the primary reasons for the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication with antibiotics is an unsuitable way of using them but a common practice in resource-constrained countries.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The practice exposes individuals to the risk of bacteria that have developed antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Many people resort to this out of necessity, when access to a physician is unavailable, or when patients have a limited amount of time or money to see a doctor.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This increased access makes it extremely easy to obtain antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] An example is India, where in the state of Punjab 73% of the population resorted to treating their minor health issues and chronic illnesses through self-medication.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication is higher outside the hospital environment.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The prevalence of self-medication in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs) ranges from 8.1% to 93%.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Accessibility, affordability, and conditions of health facilities, as well as the health-seeking behavior, are factors that influence self-medication in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] To determine the public's knowledge and preconceived notions on antibiotic resistance, a screening of 3,537 articles published in Europe, Asia, and North America was done.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Of the 55,225 total people surveyed in the articles, 70% had heard of antibiotic resistance previously, but 88% of those people thought it referred to some type of physical change in the human body.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Clinical misuse by healthcare professionals is another contributor to increased antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Studies done in the US show that the indication for treatment of antibiotics, choice of the agent used, and the duration of therapy was incorrect in up to 50% of the cases studied.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2010 and 2011 about a third of antibiotic prescriptions in outpatient settings in the United States were not necessary.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Another study in an intensive care unit in a major hospital in France has shown that 30% to 60% of prescribed antibiotics were unnecessary.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These inappropriate uses of antimicrobial agents promote the evolution of antimicrobial resistance by supporting the bacteria in developing genetic alterations that lead to resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This demonstrates that many doctors underestimate the impact that their own prescribing habits have on antimicrobial resistance as a whole.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It also confirms that some physicians may be overly cautious and prescribe antibiotics for both medical or legal reasons, even when clinical indications for use of these medications are not always confirmed.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This can lead to unnecessary antimicrobial use, a pattern which may have worsened during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Studies have shown that common misconceptions about the effectiveness and necessity of antibiotics to treat common mild illnesses contribute to their overuse.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Important to the conversation of antibiotic use is the veterinary medical system.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Veterinary oversight is required by law for all medically important antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Veterinarians use the Pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic model (PK/PD) approach to ensuring that the correct dose of the drug is delivered to the correct place at the correct timing.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Increased antibiotic use during the early waves of the COVID-19 pandemic may exacerbate this global health challenge.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Moreover, pandemic burdens on some healthcare systems may contribute to antibiotic-resistant infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The use of disinfectants such as alcohol-based hand sanitizers, and antiseptic hand wash may also have the potential to increase antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Overuse of disinfectants can lead to mutations that induce antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] On the other hand, "increased hand hygiene, decreased international travel, and decreased elective hospital procedures may have reduced AMR pathogen selection and spread in the short term" during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Critically ill patients are prone to infections, and because of that, they often require antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The more antimicrobials, the more resistance one becomes to it.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) significantly strains healthcare systems and national economies.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The World Bank estimates that by 2050, AMR could increase healthcare costs by around US$1 trillion and cause global economic losses of US$1‚Äì3.4 trillion annually by 2030.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistant infections are harder to treat, often requiring longer hospital stays, additional tests, and stronger, more expensive medications, placing extra pressure on hospitals and health systems, especially during pandemics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A 2024 United Nations High-Level Meeting on AMR has pledged to reduce deaths associated with bacterial AMR by 10% over the next six years.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In their first major declaration on the issue since 2016, global leaders also committed to raising $100 million to update and implement AMR action plans.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, the final draft of the declaration omitted an earlier target to reduce antibiotic use in animals by 30% by 2030, due to opposition from meat-producing countries and the farming industry.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Critics argue this omission is a major weakness, as livestock accounts for around 73% of global sales of antimicrobial agents, including antibiotics, antivirals, and antiparasitics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Considering the complex interactions between humans, animals and the environment, it is also important to consider the environmental aspects and contributors to antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One of these factors is human and hospital waste, which is a substantial contributor to environmental antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It is estimated that around 50‚Äì80% of antibiotics are passed unmetabolized in urine and 4‚Äì30% in feces, causing large quantities of active antibiotics to enter sewage systems.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Sewage environments contain high levels of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria (ARB), antimicrobial resistance genes (ARGs), and mobile genetic elements such as plasmids, which enable rapid gene exchange.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs) are typically not designed to remove AMR; in some cases, multidrug-resistant species such as *Escherichia, Shigella, and Klebsiella* can increase twofold in treated wastewater.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) has also been detected in both raw and treated sewage.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Agriculture is also a major contributor to environmental AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Manure from livestock (such as cattle, sheep, etc.) contains residual antibiotics, which enter the soil as farmers usually use it as fertilizer.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These are typically at levels of 1‚Äì10 mg/kg, and also contain ARBs and ARGs.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One megaton of antibiotics has been estimated to have entered global soils through manure application.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Pathogens can survive in soil for up to 10 years and on plant surfaces for up to 1 year, thereby enabling long-term environmental continuation of AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Because manure can be applied to diverse crops, residual antibiotics and resistance genes can enter plant tissues and the surrounding soil microbiota, contributing to AMR detected on fruits and vegetables.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Heavy metals in soil, often introduced through fertilizers or industrial processes, can drive cross- and co-resistance mechanisms that select for antibiotic-resistant bacteria even when no antibiotics are present.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Similar selective results happen with biocides and pesticides.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Aquaculture is an underrecognized source of environmental AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Approximately 70% of antibiotics administered in aquaculture enter surrounding waterways, and tetracycline-resistant genes have been found even in isolated environments such as Antarctica and the Arctic.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic usage varies substantially across countries, showing the major differences in regulatory oversight.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] High antibiotic use in many Asian aquaculture systems has added to the elevated levels of clinically important resistance genes in sediments and river systems.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Recent research has shown that AMR also occurs through the air.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Airborne resistance genes have been detected at high levels in major urban centers, and farms have been determined as hotspots for airborne AMR, with resistance markers detected in the air surrounding animal operations.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The antimicrobial resistance crisis also extends to the food industry, specifically with food producing animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] With an ever-increasing human population, there is constant pressure to intensify productivity in many agricultural sectors, including the production of meat as a source of protein.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotics are fed to livestock to act as growth supplements, and a preventive measure to decrease the likelihood of infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Farmers typically use antibiotics in animal feed to improve growth rates and prevent infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, this is illogical as antibiotics are used to treat infections and not prevent infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agricultural purposes and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Overusing antibiotics gives the bacteria time to adapt leaving higher doses or even stronger antibiotics needed to combat the infection.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Though antibiotics for growth promotion were banned throughout the EU in 2006, 40 countries still use antibiotics to promote growth.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This can result in the transfer of resistant bacterial strains into the food that humans eat, causing potentially fatal transfer of disease.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While the practice of using antibiotics as growth promoters does result in better yields and meat products, it is a major issue and needs to be decreased to prevent antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Though the evidence linking antimicrobial usage in livestock to antimicrobial resistance is limited, the World Health Organization Advisory Group on Integrated Surveillance of Antimicrobial Resistance strongly recommended the reduction of use of medically important antimicrobials in livestock.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Additionally, the Advisory Group stated that such antimicrobials should be expressly prohibited for both growth promotion and disease prevention in food producing animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] By mapping antimicrobial consumption in livestock, it was predicted that in 228 countries there would be a total 67% increase in consumption of antibiotics by livestock by 2030.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In some countries such as Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa it is predicted that a 99% increase will occur.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Several countries have restricted the use of antibiotics in livestock, including Canada, China, Japan, and the US.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These restrictions are sometimes associated with a reduction of the prevalence of antimicrobial resistance in humans.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Most pesticides protect crops against insects and plants, but in some cases antimicrobial pesticides are used to protect against various microorganisms such as bacteria, viruses, fungi, algae, and protozoa.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The overuse of many pesticides in an effort to have a higher yield of crops has resulted in many of these microbes evolving a tolerance against these antimicrobial agents.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Currently there are over 4000 antimicrobial pesticides registered with the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and sold to market, showing the widespread use of these agents.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It is estimated that for every single meal a person consumes, 0.3 g of pesticides is used, as 90% of all pesticide use is in agriculture.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A majority of these products are used to help defend against the spread of infectious diseases, and hopefully protect public health.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] But out of the large amount of pesticides used, it is also estimated that less than 0.1% of those antimicrobial agents, actually reach their targets.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] That leaves over 99% of all pesticides used available to contaminate other resources.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In soil, air, and water these antimicrobial agents are able to spread, coming in contact with more microorganisms and leading to these microbes evolving mechanisms to tolerate and further resist pesticides.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The use of antifungal azole pesticides that drive environmental azole resistance have been linked to azole resistance cases in the clinical setting.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The same issues confront the novel antifungal classes (e.g. orotomides) which are again being used in both the clinic and agriculture.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wildlife, including wild and migratory birds, serve as indicators of ecosystem health.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] They act as a reservoir for zoonotic diseases and antimicrobial-resistant organisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Birds are a key link between the transmission of zoonotic diseases to human populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] By the same token, increased contact between wild birds and human populations (including domesticated animals), has increased the amount of anti-microbial resistance (AMR) to the bird population.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The introduction of AMR to wild birds positively correlates with human pollution and increased human contact.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Additionally, wild birds can participate in horizontal gene transfer with bacteria, leading to the transmission of antibiotic-resistant genes (ARG).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For simplicity, wild bird populations can be divided into two major categories, wild sedentary birds and wild migrating birds.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wild sedentary bird exposure to AMR is through increased contact with densely populated areas, human waste, domestic animals, and domestic animal/livestock waste.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Especially if they are predators, wild, sedentary birds can come into contact with prey that interact more closely with humans.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wild migrating birds interact with sedentary birds in different environments along their migration route.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This increases the rate and diversity of AMR across varying ecosystems.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Neglect of wildlife in the global discussions surrounding health security and AMR, creates large barriers to true AMR surveillance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The surveillance of antimicrobial-resistant resistant organisms in wild birds is a potential metric for the rate of AMR in the environment.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This surveillance also allows for further investigation into the transmission routes between different ecosystems and human populations (including domesticated animals and livestock).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Such information gathered from wild bird biomes, can help identify patterns of diseased transmission and better target interventions.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These targeted interventions can inform the use of antimicrobial agents and reduce the persistence of multidrug resistant organisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Recent studies demonstrate the importance of wild birds as sentinels for AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For example, *Escherichia coli* isolated from free-ranging Bonelli's eagles (*Aquila fasciata*) in eastern Spain showed that 53.3% of isolates were resistant to at least one antimicrobial, and 29.3% were multidrug-resistant, despite the species' minimal exposure to human-associated environments.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The study also reported resistance to colistin and meropenem, two last-resort antibiotics, and documented 19 different multidrug-resistance patterns, suggesting persistent and heterogeneous selective pressures in the environment.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Because Bonelli's eagles live far from humans and urban areas, they acquire resistance largely through interactions with prey species that interact with humans.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These findings demonstrate how AMR can spread into remote ecosystems via indirect pathways, strengthening the role of wild birds, particularly apex predators, as effective bioindicators in AMR surveillance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Permafrost is a term used to refer to any ground that remained frozen for two years or more, with the oldest known examples continuously frozen for around 700,000 years.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In the recent decades, permafrost has been rapidly thawing due to climate change.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The cold preserves any organic matter inside the permafrost, and it is possible for microorganisms to resume their life functions once it thaws.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While some common pathogens such as influenza, smallpox or the bacteria associated with pneumonia have failed to survive intentional attempts to revive them, more cold-adapted microorganisms such as anthrax, or several ancient plant and amoeba viruses, have successfully survived prolonged thaw.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Some scientists have argued that the inability of known causative agents of contagious diseases to survive being frozen and thawed makes this threat unlikely.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Instead, there have been suggestions that when modern pathogenic bacteria interact with the ancient ones, they may, through horizontal gene transfer, pick up genetic sequences which are associated with antimicrobial resistance, exacerbating an already difficult issue.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotics to which permafrost bacteria have displayed at least some resistance include chloramphenicol, streptomycin, kanamycin, gentamicin, tetracycline, spectinomycin and neomycin.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, other studies show that resistance levels in ancient bacteria to modern antibiotics remain lower than in the contemporary bacteria from the active layer of thawed ground above them, which may mean that this risk is "no greater" than from any other soil.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] There have been increasing public calls for global collective action to address the threat, including a proposal for an international treaty on antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Further detail and attention is still needed to recognize and measure trends in resistance on the international level; the idea of a global tracking system has been suggested but implementation has yet to occur.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A system of this nature would provide insight to areas of high resistance as well as information necessary for evaluating programs, introducing interventions and other changes made to fight or reverse antibiotic resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) is commonly described within a *One Health* framework, which emphasizes the interconnected relationships between human health, animal health, and the environment.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial use in clinical medicine, veterinary practice, and agriculture has been associated with the selection and spread of resistant microorganisms across these sectors.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Research indicates that resistant bacteria and antimicrobial resistance genes can move between humans, animals, and environmental reservoirs through multiple pathways, including food production systems, direct contact, and exposure to contaminated water or soil.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These pathways contribute to the persistence and wider dissemination of antimicrobial resistance beyond individual settings.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Environmental sources have been increasingly examined in relation to AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Wastewater systems, agricultural runoff, and pharmaceutical residues have been identified as potential reservoirs where resistant microorganisms and resistance genes may persist.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Such reservoirs may facilitate ongoing transmission between environmental, animal, and human populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Efforts to address AMR within a One Health framework typically involve coordinated strategies across sectors, including antimicrobial stewardship, infection prevention and control, and improvements in sanitation and hygiene.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Evidence from systematic reviews suggests that interventions such as farm biosecurity and water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) practices may reduce antimicrobial use and contribute to limiting the development and spread of resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Delaying or minimizing the use of antibiotics for certain conditions may help safely reduce their use.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial treatment duration should be based on the infection and other health problems a person may have.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For many infections once a person has improved there is little evidence that stopping treatment causes more resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some, therefore, feel that stopping early may be reasonable in some cases.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Other infections, however, do require long courses regardless of whether a person feels better.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Delaying antibiotics for ailments such as a sore throat and otitis media may have no difference in the rate of complications compared with immediate antibiotics, for example.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] When treating respiratory tract infections, clinical judgement is required as to the appropriate treatment (delayed or immediate antibiotic use).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] ResistanceOpen is an online global map of antimicrobial resistance developed by HealthMap which displays aggregated data on antimicrobial resistance from publicly available and user submitted data.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The website can display data for a 25 miles (40 km) radius from a location.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Users may submit data from antibiograms for individual hospitals or laboratories.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] European data is from the EARS-Net (European Antimicrobial Resistance Surveillance Network), part of the ECDC.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] ResistanceMap is a website by the Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy and provides data on antimicrobial resistance on a global level.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO's AMR global action plan also recommends antimicrobial resistance surveillance in animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Initial steps in the EU for establishing the veterinary counterpart EARS-Vet (EARS-Net for veterinary medicine) have been made.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] AMR data from pets in particular is scarce, but needed to support antibiotic stewardship in veterinary medicine.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] By comparison there is a lack of national and international monitoring programs for antifungal resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship programmes appear useful in reducing rates of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The antimicrobial stewardship program will also provide pharmacists with the knowledge to educate patients that antibiotics will not work for a virus for example.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Excessive antimicrobial use has become one of the top contributors to the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Since the beginning of the antimicrobial era, antimicrobials have been used to treat a wide range of infectious diseases.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Overuse of antimicrobials has become the primary cause of rising levels of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Prescribers are willing to prescribe antimicrobials to individuals who believe that antimicrobials can cure nearly all illnesses, including viral infections like the common cold.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In an analysis of drug prescriptions, 36% of individuals with a cold or an upper respiratory infection (both usually viral in origin) were given prescriptions for antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These prescriptions increase the risk of further evolution of antibiotic resistant bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Using antimicrobials without prescription is another driving force leading to the overuse of antibiotics to self-treat diseases like the common cold, cough, fever, and dysentery resulting in an epidemic of antibiotic resistance in countries like Bangladesh, risking its spread around the globe.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Introducing strict antibiotic stewardship in the outpatient setting to reduce inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics may reduce the emerging bacterial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO AWaRe (Access, Watch, Reserve) guidance and antibiotic book has been introduced to guide antibiotic choice for the 30 most common infections in adults and children to reduce inappropriate prescribing in primary care and hospitals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Narrow-spectrum antibiotics are preferred due to their lower resistance potential, and broad-spectrum antibiotics are only recommended for people with more severe symptoms.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some antibiotics are more likely to confer resistance, so are kept as reserve antibiotics in the AWaRe book.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Various diagnostic strategies have been employed to prevent the overuse of antifungal therapy in the clinic, proving a safe alternative to empirical antifungal therapy, and thus underpinning antifungal stewardship schemes.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship teams in hospitals are encouraging optimal use of antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The goals of antimicrobial stewardship are to help practitioners pick the right drug at the right dose and duration of therapy while preventing misuse and minimizing the development of resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Stewardship interventions may reduce the length of stay by an average of slightly over 1 day while not increasing the risk of death.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Dispensing the exact number of antibiotic pharmaceutical units necessary to complete an ongoing treatment can reduce excess antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2025 cross-sectional study of 125 pharmacists at a UK NHS Foundation Trust examined knowledge, attitudes, and perceptions regarding antimicrobial stewardship following the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The study found that more than 85% of pharmacists recognized antimicrobial resistance as a public health concern.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, the pandemic created challenges, with 80% reporting that COVID-19 patient conditions influenced antibiotic prescription.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2026 systematic review of 73 studies examined arthropod-mediated pathogen transmission in hospitals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Research indicates that cockroaches, flies, and ants frequently harbor multidrug-resistant bacteria, fungi, and viruses.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] While direct causality is difficult to prove, genetic evidence links these pests to hospital-associated infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Given the volume of care provided in primary care (general practice), recent strategies have focused on reducing unnecessary antimicrobial prescribing in this setting.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Simple interventions, such as written information explaining when taking antibiotics is not necessary, for example in common infections of the upper respiratory tract, have been shown to reduce antibiotic prescribing.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Various tools are also available to help professionals decide if prescribing antimicrobials is necessary.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Parental expectations, driven by the worry for their children's health, can influence how often children are prescribed antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Parents often rely on their clinician for advice and reassurance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However a lack of plain language information and not having adequate time for consultation negatively impacts this relationship.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In effect parents often rely on past experiences in their expectations rather than reassurance from the clinician.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Adequate time for consultation and plain language information can help parents make informed decisions and avoid unnecessary antibiotic use.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The prescriber should closely adhere to the five rights of drug administration: the right patient, the right drug, the right dose, the right route, and the right time.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Microbiological samples should be taken for culture and sensitivity testing before treatment when indicated and treatment potentially changed based on the susceptibility report.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Health workers and pharmacists can help tackle antibiotic resistance by: enhancing infection prevention and control; only prescribing and dispensing antibiotics when they are truly needed; prescribing and dispensing the right antibiotic(s) to treat the illness.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A unit dose system implemented in community pharmacies can also reduce antibiotic leftovers at households.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Despite these, written guideline intervention for prescriber to do history taking and provision of advice and knowledge of pharmacists and non‚Äêpharmacists may not reduce the sales of non‚Äêprescription antimicrobial drugs in community pharmacies, drugstores, and other medicine outlets.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] People can help tackle resistance by using antibiotics only when prescribed for a bacterial infetion as well as completing the full treatment course, never sharing medication with others, and using proper disposal methods for excess drugs.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Basic hygiene practices also help prevent the spread of bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] ‚Ä¢ Germany and Sweden also have lower prescribing rates, with Sweden's rate having been declining since 2007. ‚Ä¢ Greece, France and Belgium have high prescribing rates.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Infectious disease control through improved water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) infrastructure needs to be included in the antimicrobial resistance (AMR) agenda.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Growing usage of antibiotics together with persistent infectious disease levels have led to a dangerous cycle in which reliance on antimicrobials increases while the efficacy of drugs diminishes.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The proper use of infrastructure for water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) can result in a 47‚Äì72 percent decrease of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics depending on the type of intervention and its effectiveness.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A reduction of the diarrhea disease burden through improved infrastructure would result in large decreases in the number of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This was estimated as ranging from 5 million in Brazil to up to 590 million in India by the year 2030.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The strong link between increased consumption and resistance indicates that this will directly mitigate the accelerating spread of AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Sanitation and water for all by 2030 is Goal Number 6 of the Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] An increase in hand washing compliance by hospital staff results in decreased rates of resistant organisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Water supply and sanitation infrastructure in health facilities offer opportunities for combatting AMR, and investment should be increased.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There is much room for improvement: WHO and UNICEF estimated in 2015 that 38% of health facilities did not have a source of water, nearly 19% had no toilets and 35% had no water and soap or alcohol-based hand rub for handwashing.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Manufacturers of antimicrobials need to improve the treatment of their wastewater (by using industrial wastewater treatment processes) to reduce the release of residues into the environment.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It is established that the use of antibiotics in animal husbandry can give rise to AMR resistances in bacteria found in food animals to the antibiotics being administered (through injections or medicated feeds).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For this reason only antimicrobials that are deemed "not-clinically relevant" are used in these practices.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Unlike resistance to antibacterials, antifungal resistance can be driven by arable farming, currently there is no regulation on the use of similar antifungal classes in agriculture and the clinic.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent studies have shown that the prophylactic use of "non-priority" or "non-clinically relevant" antimicrobials in feeds can potentially, under certain conditions, lead to co-selection of environmental AMR bacteria with resistance to medically important antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The possibility for co-selection of AMR resistances in the food chain pipeline may have far-reaching implications for human health.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 1997, European Union health ministers voted to ban avoparcin and four additional antibiotics used to promote animal growth in 1999.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2006 a ban on the use of antibiotics in European feed, with the exception of two antibiotics in poultry feeds, became effective.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In Scandinavia, there is evidence that the ban has led to a lower prevalence of antibiotic resistance in (nonhazardous) animal bacterial populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] As of 2004, several European countries established a decline of antimicrobial resistance in humans through limiting the use of antimicrobials in agriculture and food industries without jeopardizing animal health or economic cost.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) collect data on antibiotic use in humans and in a more limited fashion in animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] About 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agriculture purposes, and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This gives reason for concern about the antibiotic resistance crisis in the U.S. and more reason to monitor it.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The FDA first determined in 1977 that there is evidence of emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains in livestock.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The long-established practice of permitting OTC sales of antibiotics (including penicillin and other drugs) to lay animal owners for administration to their own animals nonetheless continued in all states.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2000, the FDA announced their intention to revoke approval of fluoroquinolone use in poultry production because of substantial evidence linking it to the emergence of fluoroquinolone-resistant *Campylobacter* infections in humans.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Legal challenges from the food animal and pharmaceutical industries delayed the final decision to do so until 2006.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Fluroquinolones have been banned from extra-label use in food animals in the USA since 2007.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, they are still used in treatment of companion and exotic animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The increasing interconnectedness of the world and the fact that new classes of antibiotics have not been developed and approved for 25 years highlight the extent to which antimicrobial resistance is a global health challenge.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A global action plan to tackle the growing problem of resistance to antibiotics and other antimicrobial medicines was endorsed at the Sixty-eighth World Health Assembly in May 2015.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One of the key objectives of the plan is to improve awareness and understanding of antimicrobial resistance through effective communication, education and training.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This global action plan developed by the World Health Organization was created to combat the issue of antimicrobial resistance and was guided by the advice of countries and key stakeholders.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO's global action plan is composed of five key objectives that can be targeted through different means, and represents countries coming together to solve a major problem that can have future health consequences.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The World Health Organization has promoted the first World Antibiotic Awareness Week running from 16 to 22 November 2015.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The aim of the week is to increase global awareness of antibiotic resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It also wants to promote the correct usage of antibiotics across all fields to prevent further instances of antibiotic resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] World Antibiotic Awareness Week has been held every November since 2015.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For 2017, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), the World Health Organization (WHO) and the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) are together calling for responsible use of antibiotics in humans and animals to reduce the emergence of antibiotic resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2016 the Secretary-General of the United Nations convened the Interagency Coordination Group (IACG) on Antimicrobial Resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The IACG worked with international organizations and experts in human, animal, and plant health to create a plan to fight antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Their report released in April 2019 focuses on the seriousness of antimicrobial resistance and the threat it poses to world health.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It suggests five recommendations for member states to follow to tackle this increasing threat.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The **One Health** approach recognizes that human, animal, and environmental health are interconnected in the development and spread of antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Alteration of target- or binding site: for example, alteration of PBP‚Äîthe binding target site of penicillins‚Äîin MRSA and other penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Another protective mechanism found among bacterial species is ribosomal protection proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These proteins protect the bacterial cell from antibiotics that target the cell's ribosomes to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The mechanism involves the binding of the ribosomal protection proteins to the ribosomes of the bacterial cell, which in turn changes its conformational shape.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This allows the ribosomes to continue synthesizing proteins essential to the cell while preventing antibiotics from binding to the ribosome to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Reduced drug accumulation: by decreasing drug permeability or increasing active efflux (pumping out) of the drugs across the cell surface.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These multidrug efflux pumps within the cellular membrane of certain bacterial species are used to pump antibiotics out of the cell before they are able to do any damage.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] They are often activated by a specific substrate associated with an antibiotic, as in fluoroquinolone resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Ribosome splitting and recycling: for example, drug-mediated stalling of the ribosome by lincomycin and erythromycin unstalled by a heat shock protein found in *Listeria monocytogenes*, which is a homologue of HflX from other bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Liberation of the ribosome from the drug allows further translation and consequent resistance to the drug.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There are several different types of germs that have developed a resistance over time.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The six pathogens causing most deaths associated with resistance are *Escherichia coli*, *Staphylococcus aureus, Klebsiella pneumoniae, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Acinetobacter baumannii*, and *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] They were responsible for 929,000 deaths attributable to resistance and 3.57 million deaths associated with resistance in 2019.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Penicillinase-producing *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* developed a resistance to penicillin in 1976.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Another example is Azithromycin-resistant *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, which developed a resistance to azithromycin in 2011.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In gram-negative bacteria, plasmid-mediated resistance genes produce proteins that can bind to DNA gyrase, protecting it from the action of quinolones.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Finally, mutations at key sites in DNA gyrase or topoisomerase IV can decrease their binding affinity to quinolones, decreasing the drug's effectiveness.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some bacteria are naturally resistant to certain antibiotics; for example, gram-negative bacteria are resistant to most Œ≤-lactam antibiotics due to the presence of Œ≤-lactamase.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antibiotic resistance can also be acquired as a result of either genetic mutation or horizontal gene transfer.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Although mutations are rare, with spontaneous mutations in the pathogen genome occurring at a rate of about 1 in 105 to 1 in 108 per chromosomal replication, Bacteria reproduce at a high rate, lifespans and production of new generations can be on a timescale of mere hours.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A new (de novo) mutation in a parent cell can quickly become an inherited mutation of widespread prevalence, resulting in the microevolution of a fully resistant colony.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, chromosomal mutations also confer a cost of fitness.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For example, a ribosomal mutation may protect a bacterial cell by changing the binding site of an antibiotic but may result in slower growth rate.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Moreover, some adaptive mutations can propagate not only through inheritance but also through horizontal gene transfer.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The most common mechanism of horizontal gene transfer is the transferring of plasmids carrying antibiotic resistance genes between bacteria of the same or different species via conjugation.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent findings show no necessity of large populations of bacteria for the appearance of antibiotic resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Small populations of *Escherichia coli* in an antibiotic gradient can become resistant.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Any heterogeneous environment with respect to nutrient and antibiotic gradients may facilitate antibiotic resistance in small bacterial populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Researchers hypothesize that the mechanism of resistance evolution is based on four SNP mutations in the genome of *E. coli* produced by the gradient of antibiotic.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In one study, which has implications for space microbiology, a non-pathogenic strain *E. coli* MG1655 was exposed to trace levels of the broad spectrum antibiotic chloramphenicol, under simulated microgravity (LSMMG, or Low Shear Modeled Microgravity) over 1000 generations.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Thus, irrespective of where they are used, the use of an antibiotic would likely result in persistent resistance to that antibiotic, as well as cross-resistance to other antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In recent years, the emergence and spread of Œ≤-lactamases called carbapenemases has become a major health crisis.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One such carbapenemase is New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase 1 (NDM-1), an enzyme that makes bacteria resistant to a broad range of beta-lactam antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The most common bacteria that make this enzyme are gram-negative such as *E. coli* and *Klebsiella pneumoniae*, but the gene for NDM-1 can spread from one strain of bacteria to another by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Specific antiviral drugs are used to treat some viral infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These drugs prevent viruses from reproducing by inhibiting essential stages of the virus's replication cycle in infected cells.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antivirals are used to treat HIV, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, influenza, herpes viruses including varicella zoster virus, cytomegalovirus and Epstein‚ÄìBarr virus.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] With each virus, some strains have become resistant to the administered drugs.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antiviral drugs typically target key components of viral reproduction; for example, oseltamivir targets influenza neuraminidase,while guanosine analogs inhibit viral DNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to antivirals is thus acquired through mutations in the genes that encode the protein targets of the drugs.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to HIV antivirals is problematic, and even multi-drug resistant strains have evolved.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One source of resistance is that many current HIV drugs, including NRTIs and NNRTIs, target reverse transcriptase; however, HIV-1 reverse transcriptase is highly error prone and thus mutations conferring resistance arise rapidly.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistant strains of the HIV virus emerge rapidly if only one antiviral drug is used.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Using three or more drugs together, termed combination therapy, has helped to control this problem, but new drugs are needed because of the continuing emergence of drug-resistant HIV strains.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Infections by fungi are a cause of high morbidity and mortality in immunocompromised persons, such as those with HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis or receiving chemotherapy.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The fungi *Candida*, *Cryptococcus neoformans* and *Aspergillus fumigatus* cause most of these infections and antifungal resistance occurs in all of them.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Multidrug resistance in fungi is increasing because of the widespread use of antifungal drugs to treat infections in immunocompromised individuals and the use of some agricultural antifungals.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistant disease is associated with increased mortality.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some fungi (for example, *Candida krusei* and fluconazole) exhibit intrinsic resistance to certain antifungal drugs or classes, whereas some species develop antifungal resistance to external pressures.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistance is a One Health concern, driven by multiple extrinsic factors, including overuse of fungicides, clinical antifungals, environmental change and host factors.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In the USA fluconazole-resistant Candida species and azole resistance in Aspergillus fumigatus have been highlighted as a growing threat.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] 20 species of *Candida* can cause candidiasis infection, the most common of which is *Candida albicans*.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] *Candida* yeasts normally inhabit the skin and mucous membranes without causing infection.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, overgrowth of *Candida* can lead to candidiasis.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] *Candida glabrata)* are becoming resistant to first-line and second-line antifungal agents such as echinocandins and azoles.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The emergence of *Candida auris* as a potential human pathogen that sometimes exhibits multi-class antifungal drug resistance is concerning and has been associated with several outbreaks.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO has released a priority fungal pathogen list, including pathogens with antifungal resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The identification of antifungal resistance is undermined by limited classical diagnosis of infection, where a culture is lacking, preventing susceptibility testing.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] National and international surveillance schemes for fungal disease and antifungal resistance are limited, hampering the understanding of the disease burden and associated resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The application of molecular testing to identify genetic markers associating with resistance may improve the identification of antifungal resistance, but the diversity of mutations associated with resistance is increasing across the fungal species causing infection.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In addition, a number of resistance mechanisms depend on up-regulation of selected genes (for instance reflux pumps) rather than defined mutations that are amenable to molecular detection.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Due to the limited number of antifungals in clinical use and the increasing global incidence of antifungal resistance, using the existing antifungals in combination might be beneficial in some cases but further research is needed.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Similarly, other approaches that might help to combat the emergence of antifungal resistance could rely on the development of host-directed therapies such as immunotherapy or vaccines.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The protozoan parasites that cause the diseases malaria, trypanosomiasis, toxoplasmosis, cryptosporidiosis and leishmaniasis are important human pathogens.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Malarial parasites that are resistant to the drugs that are currently available to infections are common and this has led to increased efforts to develop new drugs.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to recently developed drugs such as artemisinin has also been reported.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The problem of drug resistance in malaria has driven efforts to develop vaccines.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Trypanosomes are parasitic protozoa that cause African trypanosomiasis and Chagas disease (American trypanosomiasis).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There are no vaccines to prevent these infections so drugs such as pentamidine and suramin, benznidazole and nifurtimox are used to treat infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These drugs are effective but infections caused by resistant parasites have been reported.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Leishmaniasis is caused by protozoa and is a public health problem in sub-tropical and tropical countries.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Drug resistance has "become a major concern".
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The preferred treatment for leishmaniasis regionally; liposomal amphotericin B is used in the Mediterranean basin and pentavalent antimonials are more commonly used in Africa, South America, Bangladesh, India, and Nepal.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to antibiotics in *Leishmania* is a relatively recent phenomena.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The first reported instance of resistance to antimonials was reported in India in the 1980s.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2022, genomic epidemiologists reported results from a global survey of antimicrobial resistance via genomic wastewater-based epidemiology, finding large regional variations, providing maps, and suggesting resistance genes are also passed on between microbial species that are not closely related.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO provides the Global Antimicrobial Resistance and Use Surveillance System (GLASS) reports which summarize annual (e.g.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] 2020's) data on international AMR, also including an interactive dashboard.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Public Health England reported that the total number of antibiotic resistant infections in England rose by 9% from 55,812 in 2017 to 60,788 in 2018, but antibiotic consumption had fallen by 9% from 20.0 to 18.2 defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants per day between 2014 and 2018.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that 2.8 million cases of antibiotic resistance have been reported.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, in 2019 overall deaths from antibiotic-resistant infections decreased by 18% and deaths in hospitals decreased by 30%.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The COVID pandemic caused a reversal of much of the progress made on attenuating the effects of antibiotic resistance, resulting in more antibiotic use, more resistant infections, and less data on preventive action.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Hospital-onset infections and deaths both increased by 15% in 2020, and significantly higher rates of infections were reported for 4 out of 6 types of healthcare associated infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Owing to rampant misuse, over-prescription, and unregulated over-the-counter access to antibiotics, the growth of AMR superbugs has proliferated in India.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Pharmacies surveyed by the Karnataka government revealed that 80% of drugs were being sold without a prescription.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2019, India reported 300,000 deaths because of infections relating to AMR, India also reports the most number of tuberculosis cases resistant to antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The 1950s to 1970s represented the golden age of antibiotic discovery, where countless new classes of antibiotics were discovered to treat previously incurable diseases such as tuberculosis and syphilis.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, since that time the discovery of new classes of antibiotics has been almost nonexistent, and represents a situation that is especially problematic considering the resiliency of bacteria shown over time and the continued misuse and overuse of antibiotics in treatment.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Already in 1940, in their letter to the editor of Nature journal, Abraham and Chain identified the enzyme penicillinase as responsible for the deactivation of penicillin in penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This discovery was the first step in understanding the mechanisms of microbial resistance to Œ≤-lactam antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The phenomenon of antimicrobial resistance caused by overuse of antibiotics was predicted as early as 1945 by Alexander Fleming who said "The time may come when penicillin can be bought by anyone in the shops.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance can lead to epidemics of enormous proportions if preventive actions are not taken.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In this day and age current antimicrobial resistance leads to longer hospital stays, higher medical costs, and increased mortality.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Since the mid-1980s pharmaceutical companies have invested in medications for cancer or chronic disease that have greater potential to make money and have "de-emphasized or dropped development of antibiotics".
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] On 20 January 2016 at the World Economic Forum, "80 pharmaceutical and diagnostic companies" called for "transformational commercial models" at an international level to spur research and development on antibiotics and on the use of diagnostic tests.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A number of countries are considering or implementing delinked payment models for new antimicrobials whereby payment is based on value rather than volume of drug sales.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This offers the opportunity to pay for valuable new drugs even if they are reserved for use in relatively rare drug resistant infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some global health scholars have argued that a global, legal framework is needed to prevent and control antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For instance, binding global policies could be used to create antimicrobial use standards, regulate antibiotic marketing, and strengthen global surveillance systems.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Ensuring compliance of involved parties is a challenge.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For the United States 2016 budget, U.S. president Barack Obama proposed to nearly double the amount of federal funding to "combat and prevent" antibiotic resistance to $1.2 billion.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Many international funding agencies like USAID, DFID, Sida and Gates Foundation have pledged money for developing strategies to counter antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] On 27 March 2015, the White House released a plan to address the increasing need for agencies to combat the rise of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Task Force for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria developed *The National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria* with the intent of providing a roadmap to guide the US in the antibiotic resistance challenge and with hopes of saving many lives.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This plan outlines steps taken by the Federal government over the next five years needed to prevent and contain outbreaks of antibiotic-resistant infections; maintain the efficacy of antibiotics already on the market; and to help to develop future diagnostics, antibiotics, and vaccines.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Action Plan was developed around five goals with focuses on strengthening health care, public health veterinary medicine, agriculture, food safety and research, and manufacturing.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] As of 2023, AMR remains a public health threat in the United States.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's 2023 Report on Antibiotic Resistance Threats, over 2.8 million antibiotic-resistant infections occur in the U.S. each year, leading to at least 35,000 deaths annually.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Among the most concerning resistant pathogens are Carbapenem-resistant *Enterobacteriaceae* (CRE), Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA), and *Clostridioides difficile* (C. diff), all of which continue to be responsible for severe healthcare-associated infections (HAIs).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic led to a disruption in healthcare, with an increase in the use of antibiotics during the treatment of viral infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This rise in antibiotic prescribing, coupled with overwhelmed healthcare systems, contributed to a resurgence in AMR during the pandemic years.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2021 CDC report identified a sharp increase in HAIs caused by resistant pathogens in COVID-19 patients, a trend that has persisted into 2023.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent data suggest that although antibiotic use has decreased since the pandemic, some resistant pathogens remain prevalent in healthcare settings.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The CDC has also expanded its Get Ahead of Sepsis campaign in 2023, focusing on raising awareness of AMR's role in sepsis and promoting the judicious use of antibiotics in both healthcare and community settings.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This initiative has reached millions through social media, healthcare facilities, and public health outreach, aiming to educate the public on the importance of preventing infections and reducing antibiotic misuse.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Trump, severe federal funding cuts in 2025 at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and many other research entities in the United States are expected to impede progress in combating antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Public health experts believe these budget reductions will adversely affect the development of new antibiotics as well as advances in diagnostics and treatment strategies, thus undermining efforts currently underway to address AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) is but one organization that has expressed grave concern regarding the negative consequences of such extreme budget measures on antimicrobial stewardship, and, as a result, on global health security overall.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] According to World Health Organization, policymakers can help tackle resistance by strengthening resistance-tracking and laboratory capacity and by regulating and promoting the appropriate use of medicines.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Policymakers and industry can help tackle resistance by: fostering research and development of new tools and promoting cooperation and information sharing among all stakeholders.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The U.S. government continues to prioritize AMR mitigation through policy and legislation.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2023, the National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria (CARB) 2023-2028 was released, outlining strategic objectives for reducing antibiotic-resistant infections, advancing infection prevention, and accelerating research on new antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The plan also emphasizes the importance of improving antibiotic stewardship across healthcare, agriculture, and veterinary settings.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Furthermore, the PASTEUR Act (Pioneering Antimicrobial Subscriptions to End Upsurging Resistance) has gained momentum in Congress.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] If passed, the bill would create a subscription-based payment model to incentivize the development of new antimicrobial drugs, while supporting antimicrobial stewardship programs to reduce the misuse of existing antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This legislation is considered a critical step toward addressing the economic barriers to developing new antimicrobials.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Measuring the costs and benefits of strategies to combat AMR is difficult and policies may only have effects in the distant future.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In other infectious diseases this problem has been addressed by using mathematical models.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] More research is needed to understand how AMR develops and spreads so that mathematical modelling can be used to anticipate the likely effects of different policies.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Distinguishing infections requiring antibiotics from self-limiting ones is clinically challenging.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] To guide appropriate use of antibiotics and prevent the evolution and spread of antimicrobial resistance, diagnostic tests that provide clinicians with timely, actionable results are needed.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Acute fever is a common reason for seeking medical care and a major cause of morbidity and mortality.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Multiple studies have shown that the use of malaria rapid diagnostic tests without reliable tools to distinguish other fever causes has resulted in increased antibiotic use.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) can facilitate a precision medicine approach to treatment by helping clinicians to prescribe more effective and targeted antimicrobial therapy.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] At the same time with traditional phenotypic AST it can take 12 to 48 hours to obtain a result due to the time taken for organisms to grow on/in culture media.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Rapid testing, possible from molecular diagnostics innovations, is defined as "being feasible within an 8-h working shift".
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] There are several commercial Food and Drug Administration-approved assays available which can detect AMR genes from a variety of specimen types.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Progress has been slow due to a range of reasons including cost and regulation.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Genotypic AMR characterisation methods are, however, being increasingly used in combination with machine learning algorithms in research to help better predict phenotypic AMR from organism genotype.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Optical techniques such as phase contrast microscopy in combination with single-cell analysis are another powerful method to monitor bacterial growth.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In 2017, scientists from Uppsala University in Sweden published a method that applies principles of microfluidics and cell tracking, to monitor bacterial response to antibiotics in less than 30 minutes overall manipulation time.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] This invention was awarded the 8M¬£ Longitude Prize on AMR in 2024.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Recently, this platform has been advanced by coupling microfluidic chip with optical tweezing to isolate bacteria with altered phenotype directly from the analytical matrix.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Rapid diagnostic methods have also been trialled as antimicrobial stewardship interventions to influence the healthcare drivers of AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Serum procalcitonin measurement has been shown to reduce mortality rate, antimicrobial consumption and antimicrobial-related side-effects in patients with respiratory infections, but impact on AMR has not yet been demonstrated.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Similarly, point of care serum testing of the inflammatory biomarker C-reactive protein has been shown to influence antimicrobial prescribing rates in this patient cohort, but further research is required to demonstrate an effect on rates of AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Clinical investigation to rule out bacterial infections are often done for patients with pediatric acute respiratory infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Currently it is unclear if rapid viral testing affects antibiotic use in children.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccines are an essential part of the response to reduce AMR as they prevent infections, reduce the use and overuse of antimicrobials, and slow the emergence and spread of drug-resistant pathogens.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Microorganisms usually do not develop resistance to vaccines because vaccines reduce the spread of the infection and target the pathogen in multiple ways in the same host and possibly in different ways between different hosts.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Furthermore, if the use of vaccines increases, there is evidence that antibiotic resistant strains of pathogens will decrease; the need for antibiotics will naturally decrease as vaccines prevent infection before it occurs.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] A 2024 report by WHO finds that vaccines against 24 pathogens could reduce the number of antibiotics needed by 22% or 2.5 billion DDD every year.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] If vaccines could be rolled out against all the evaluated pathogens, they could save a third of the hospital costs associated with AMR.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccinated people have fewer infections and are protected against potential complications from secondary infections that may need antimicrobial medicines or require admission to hospital.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, there are well documented cases of vaccine resistance, although these are usually much less of a problem than antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antistaphylococcal vaccines have shown limited efficacy, because of immunological variation between *Staphylococcus* species, and the limited duration of effectiveness of the antibodies produced.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Development and testing of more effective vaccines is underway.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Two registrational trials have evaluated vaccine candidates in active immunization strategies against *S. aureus* infection.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In a phase II trial, a bivalent vaccine of capsular proteins 5 & 8 was tested in 1804 hemodialysis patients with a primary fistula or synthetic graft vascular access.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] After 40 weeks following vaccination a protective effect was seen against *S. aureus* bacteremia, but not at 54 weeks following vaccination.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Based on these results, a second trial was conducted which failed to show efficacy.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Merck tested V710, a vaccine targeting IsdB, in a blinded randomized trial in patients undergoing median sternotomy.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The trial was terminated after a higher rate of multiorgan system failure‚Äìrelated deaths was found in the V710 recipients.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccine recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection were five times more likely to die than control recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Investigators have suggested that a multiple-antigen vaccine would be more effective, but a lack of biomarkers defining human protective immunity keep these proposals in the logical, but strictly hypothetical arena.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antibodies show evidence against antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) target bacterial virulence factors, aiding in bacterial destruction through various mechanisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Three FDA-approved antibodies target *Bacillus anthracis* and *Clostridioides difficile* toxins.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Alternating therapy is a proposed method in which two or three antibiotics are taken in a rotation versus taking just one antibiotic such that bacteria resistant to one antibiotic are killed when the next antibiotic is taken.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Studies have found that this method reduces the rate at which antibiotic resistant bacteria emerge in vitro relative to a single drug for the entire duration.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Studies have found that bacteria that evolve antibiotic resistance towards one group of antibiotic may become more sensitive to others.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] This phenomenon can be used to select against resistant bacteria using an approach termed collateral sensitivity cycling, which has recently been found to be relevant in developing treatment strategies for chronic infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Despite its promise, large-scale clinical and experimental studies revealed limited evidence of susceptibility to antibiotic cycling across various pathogens.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Another concern is that practitioners may become reluctant to perform routine surgeries because of the increased risk of harmful infection.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Backup treatments can have serious side-effects; for example, antibiotics like aminoglycosides (such as amikacin, gentamicin, kanamycin, streptomycin, etc.) used for the treatment of drug-resistant tuberculosis and cystic fibrosis can cause respiratory disorders, deafness and kidney failure.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The potential crisis at hand is the result of a marked decrease in industry research and development.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Poor financial investment in antibiotic research has exacerbated the situation.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In 2011, Pfizer, one of the last major pharmaceutical companies developing new antibiotics, shut down its primary research effort, citing poor shareholder returns relative to drugs for chronic illnesses.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, small and medium-sized pharmaceutical companies are still active in antibiotic drug research.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In particular, apart from classical synthetic chemistry methodologies, researchers have developed a combinatorial synthetic biology platform on single cell level in a high-throughput screening manner to diversify novel lanthipeptides.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In the 5‚Äì10 years since 2010, there has been a change in the ways new antimicrobial agents are discovered and developed ‚Äì principally via the formation of public-private funding initiatives.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Later stage clinical development is supported by the AMR Action Fund, which in turn is supported by multiple investors with the aim of developing 2‚Äì4 new antimicrobial agents by 2030.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The discovery and development of new antimicrobial agents has been facilitated by regulatory advances, which have been principally led by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] These processes are increasingly aligned although important differences remain and drug developers must prepare separate documents.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] New development pathways have been developed to help with the approval of new antimicrobial agents that address unmet needs such as the Limited Population Pathway for Antibacterial and Antifungal Drugs (LPAD).
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] These new pathways are required because of difficulties in conducting large definitive phase III clinical trials in a timely way.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Some of the economic impediments to the development of new antimicrobial agents have been addressed by reimbursement schemes that delink payment of antimicrobials from volume-based sales.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The available classes of antifungal drugs are still limited but as of 2021 novel classes of antifungals are being developed and are undergoing various stages of clinical trials to assess performance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Scientists have started using advanced computational approaches with supercomputers for the development of new antibiotic derivatives to deal with antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Using antibiotic-free alternatives in bone infection treatment may help decrease the use of antibiotics and thus antimicrobial resistance.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The bone regeneration material bioactive glass S53P4 has shown to effectively inhibit the bacterial growth of up to 50 clinically relevant bacteria including MRSA and MRSE.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] During the last decades, copper and silver nanomaterials have demonstrated appealing features for the development of a new family of antimicrobial agents.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Nanoparticles (1‚Äì100 nm) show unique properties and promise as antimicrobial agents against resistant bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Silver (AgNPs) and gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) are extensively studied, disrupting bacterial cell membranes and interfering with protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Zinc oxide (ZnO NPs), copper (CuNPs), and silica (SiNPs) nanoparticles also exhibit antimicrobial properties.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, high synthesis costs, potential toxicity, and instability pose challenges.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] To overcome these, biological synthesis methods and combination therapies with other antimicrobials are explored.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Similar to the situation in malaria therapy, where successful treatments based on ancient recipes have been found, there has already been some success in finding and testing ancient drugs and other treatments that are effective against AMR bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] One of the key tools identified by the WHO and others for the fight against rising antimicrobial resistance is improved surveillance of the spread and movement of AMR genes through different communities and regions.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Recent advances in high-throughput DNA sequencing as a result of the Human Genome Project have resulted in the ability to determine the individual microbial genes in a sample.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Along with the availability of databases of known antimicrobial resistance genes, such as the Comprehensive Antimicrobial Resistance Database (CARD) and ResFinder, this allows the identification of all the antimicrobial resistance genes within the sample ‚Äì the so-called "resistome".
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In doing so, a profile of these genes within a community or environment can be determined, providing information into how antimicrobial resistance is spreading through a population and allowing for the identification of resistance that is of concern.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy is the therapeutic use of bacteriophages to treat pathogenic bacterial infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy has many potential applications in human medicine as well as dentistry, veterinary science, and agriculture.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy relies on the use of naturally occurring bacteriophages to infect and lyse bacteria at the site of infection in a host.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Due to current advances in genetics and biotechnology these bacteriophages can possibly be manufactured to treat specific infections.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phages can be bioengineered to target multidrug-resistant bacterial infections, and their use involves the added benefit of preventing the elimination of beneficial bacteria in the human body.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phages destroy bacterial cell walls and membrane through the use of lytic proteins which kill bacteria by making many holes from the inside out.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophages can even possess the ability to digest the biofilm that many bacteria develop that protect them from antibiotics to effectively infect and kill bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bioengineering can play a role in creating successful bacteriophages.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Understanding the mutual interactions and evolutions of bacterial and phage populations in the environment of a human or animal body is essential for rational phage therapy.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophagics are used against antibiotic resistant bacteria in Georgia (George Eliava Institute) and in one institute in Wroc≈Çaw, Poland.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophage cocktails are common drugs sold over the counter in pharmacies in eastern countries.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In Belgium, four patients with severe musculoskeletal infections received bacteriophage therapy with concomitant antibiotics.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] After a single course of phage therapy, no recurrence of infection occurred and no severe side-effects related to the therapy were detected.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Analysing AMR data at scale requires dedicated computational approaches, as routine microbiological data from clinical laboratories can be large, heterogeneous, and subject to varying local standards.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Several open-source tools have been developed to support this work.
[src:molecular-genetics/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The AMR package for R provides functions for standardising and analysing phenotypical resistance data, including interpretation of MIC and disk diffusion results against EUCAST and CLSI breakpoints, and calculation of resistance rates across patient populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Archaeogenetics receives its name from the Greek word *arkhaios*, meaning "ancient", and the term *genetics*, meaning "the study of heredity".
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The term archaeogenetics was conceived by archaeologist Colin Renfrew.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] In February 2021, scientists reported the oldest DNA ever sequenced was successfully retrieved from a mammoth dating back over a million years.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Ludwik Hirszfeld was a Polish microbiologist and serologist who was the President of the Blood Group Section of the Second International Congress of Blood Transfusion.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] He founded blood group inheritance with Erich von Dungern in 1910, and contributed to it greatly throughout his life.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] In one of his studies in 1919, Hirszfeld documented the ABO blood groups and hair color of people at the Macedonian front, leading to his discovery that the hair color and blood type had no correlation.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] In addition to that he observed that there was a decrease of blood group A from western Europe to India and the opposite for blood group B.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] He hypothesized that the east-to-west blood group ratio stemmed from two blood groups consisting of mainly A or B mutating from blood group O, and mixing through migration or intermingling.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] A majority of his work was researching the links of blood types to sex, disease, climate, age, social class, and race.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] His work led him to discover that peptic ulcer was more dominant in blood group O, and that AB blood type mothers had a high male-to-female birth ratio.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Arthur Mourant was a British hematologist and chemist.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] He received many awards, most notably Fellowship of the Royal Society.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] His work included organizing the existing data on blood group gene frequencies, and largely contributing to the genetic map of the world through his investigation of blood groups in many populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Mourant discovered the new blood group antigens of the Lewis, Henshaw, Kell, and Rhesus systems, and analyzed the association of blood groups and various other diseases.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] He also focused on the biological significance of polymorphisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] His work provided the foundation for archaeogenetics because it facilitated the separation of genetic evidence for biological relationships between people.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This genetic evidence was previously used for that purpose.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] It also provided material that could be used to appraise the theories of population genetics.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] William Boyd was an American immunochemist and biochemist who became famous for his research on the genetics of race in the 1950s.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Renkonen independently discovered that lectins react differently to various blood types, after finding that the crude extracts of the lima bean and tufted vetch agglutinated the red blood cells from blood type A but not blood types B or O.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This ultimately led to the disclosure of thousands of plants that contained these proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] In order to examine racial differences and the distribution and migration patterns of various racial groups, Boyd systematically collected and classified blood samples from around the world, leading to his discovery that blood groups are not influenced by the environment, and are inherited.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] In his book *Genetics and the Races of Man* (1950), Boyd categorized the world population into 13 distinct races, based on their different blood type profiles and his idea that human races are populations with differing alleles.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] One of the most abundant information sources regarding inheritable traits linked to race remains the study of blood groups.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Fossil retrieval starts with selecting an excavation site.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Potential excavation sites are usually identified with the mineralogy of the location and visual detection of bones in the area.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] However, there are more ways to discover excavation zones using technology such as field portable x-ray fluorescence and Dense Stereo Reconstruction.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Tools used include knives, brushes, and pointed trowels which assist in the removal of fossils from the earth.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] To avoid contaminating the ancient DNA, specimens are handled with gloves and stored in ‚àí20 ¬∞C immediately after being unearthed.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Ensuring that the fossil sample is analyzed in a lab that has not been used for other DNA analysis could prevent contamination as well.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Bones are milled to a powder and treated with a solution before the polymerase chain reaction (PCR) process.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Samples for DNA amplification may not necessarily be fossil bones.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Preserved skin, salt-preserved or air-dried, can also be used in certain situations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] DNA preservation is difficult because the bone fossilisation degrades and DNA is chemically modified, usually by bacteria and fungi in the soil.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The best time to extract DNA from a fossil is when it is freshly out of the ground as it contains six times the DNA when compared to stored bones.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The temperature of extraction site also affects the amount of obtainable DNA, evident by a decrease in success rate for DNA amplification if the fossil is found in warmer regions.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] A drastic change of a fossil's environment also affects DNA preservation.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Since excavation causes an abrupt change in the fossil's environment, it may lead to physiochemical change in the DNA molecule.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Moreover, DNA preservation is also affected by other factors such as the treatment of the unearthed fossil like (e.g. washing, brushing and sun drying), pH, irradiation, the chemical composition of bone and soil, and hydrology.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] There are three perseveration diagenetic phases.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The first phase is bacterial putrefaction, which is estimated to cause a 15-fold degradation of DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Phase 2 is when bone chemically degrades, mostly by depurination.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The third diagenetic phase occurs after the fossil is excavated and stored, in which bone DNA degradation occurs most rapidly.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Once a specimen is collected from an archaeological site, DNA can be extracted through a series of processes.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] One of the more common methods utilizes silica and takes advantage of polymerase chain reactions in order to collect ancient DNA from bone samples.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] There are several challenges that add to the difficulty when attempting to extract ancient DNA from fossils and prepare it for analysis.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] While the organism is alive these splits are repaired; however, once an organism has died, the DNA will begin to deteriorate without repair.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This results in samples having strands of DNA measuring around 100 base pairs in length.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Contamination is another significant challenge at multiple steps throughout the process.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Often other DNA, such as bacterial DNA, will be present in the original sample.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] To avoid contamination it is necessary to take many precautions such as separate ventilation systems and workspaces for ancient DNA extraction work.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The best samples to use are fresh fossils as uncareful washing can lead to mold growth.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] DNA coming from fossils also occasionally contains a compound that inhibits DNA replication.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Coming to a consensus on which methods are best at mitigating challenges is also difficult due to the lack of repeatability caused by the uniqueness of specimens.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Silica-based DNA extraction is a method used as a purification step to extract DNA from archaeological bone artifacts and yield DNA that can be amplified using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) techniques.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This process works by using silica as a means to bind DNA and separate it from other components of the fossil process that inhibit PCR amplification.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] However, silica itself is also a strong PCR inhibitor, so careful measures must be taken to ensure that silica is removed from the DNA after extraction.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] One of the main advantages of silica-based DNA extraction is that it is relatively quick and efficient, requiring only a basic laboratory setup and chemicals.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] It is also independent of sample size, as the process can be scaled to accommodate larger or smaller quantities.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Another benefit is that the process can be executed at room temperature.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] However, this method does contain some drawbacks.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Mainly, silica-based DNA extraction can only be applied to bone and teeth samples; they cannot be used on soft tissue.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] While they work well with a variety of different fossils, they may be less effective in fossils that are not fresh (e.g. treated fossils for museums).
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Also, contamination poses a risk for all DNA replication in general, and this method may result in misleading results if applied to contaminated material.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Polymerase chain reaction is a process that can amplify segments of DNA and is often used on extracted ancient DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] It has three main steps: denaturation, annealing, and extension.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Denaturation splits the DNA into two single strands at high temperatures.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Annealing involves attaching primer strands of DNA to the single strands that allow Taq polymerase to attach to the DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Extension occurs when Taq polymerase is added to the sample and matches base pairs to turn the two single strands into two complete double strands.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This process is repeated many times, and is usually repeated a higher number of times when used with ancient DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Some issues with PCR is that it requires overlapping primer pairs for ancient DNA due to the short sequences.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] There can also be "jumping PCR" which causes recombination during the PCR process which can make analyzing the DNA more difficult in inhomogeneous samples.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] DNA extracted from fossil remains is primarily sequenced using Massive parallel sequencing, which allows simultaneous amplification and sequencing of all DNA segments in a sample, even when it is highly fragmented and of low concentration.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] It involves attaching a generic sequence to every single strand that generic primers can bond to, and thus all of the DNA present is amplified.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This is generally more costly and time intensive than PCR but due to the difficulties involved in ancient DNA amplification it is cheaper and more efficient.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] One method of massive parallel sequencing, developed by Margulies et al., employs bead-based emulsion PCR and pyrosequencing, and was found to be powerful in analyses of aDNA because it avoids potential loss of sample, substrate competition for templates, and error propagation in replication.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The most common way to analyze an aDNA sequence is to compare it with a known sequence from other sources, and this could be done in different ways for different purposes.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The identity of the fossil remain can be uncovered by comparing its DNA sequence with those of known species using software such as BLASTN.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This archaeogenetic approach is especially helpful when the morphology of the fossil is ambiguous.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Apart from that, species identification can also be done by finding specific genetic markers in an aDNA sequence.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] For example, the American indigenous population is characterized by specific mitochondrial RFLPs and deletions defined by Wallace et al.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] aDNA comparison study can also reveal the evolutionary relationship between two species.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The number of base differences between DNA of an ancient species and that of a closely related extant species can be used to estimate the divergence time of those two species from their last common ancestor.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The phylogeny of some extinct species, such as Australian marsupial wolves and American ground sloths, has been constructed by this method.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Mitochondrial DNA in animals and chloroplast DNA in plants are usually used for this purpose because they have hundreds of copies per cell and thus are more easily accessible in ancient fossils.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Another method to investigate relationship between two species is through DNA hybridization.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Single-stranded DNA segments of both species are allowed to form complementary pair bonding with each other.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] More closely related species have a more similar genetic makeup, and thus a stronger hybridization signal.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Scholz et al. conducted southern blot hybridization on Neanderthal aDNA (extracted from fossil remain W-NW and Krapina).
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The results showed weak ancient human-Neanderthal hybridization and strong ancient human-modern human hybridization.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The human-chimpanzee and Neanderthal-chimpanzee hybridization are of similarly weak strength.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This suggests that humans and Neanderthals are not as closely related as two individuals of the same species are, but they are more related to each other than to chimpanzees.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] There have also been some attempts to decipher aDNA to provide valuable phenotypic information of ancient species.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This is always done by mapping aDNA sequence onto the karyotype of a well-studied closely related species, which share a lot of similar phenotypic traits.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] For example, Green et al. compared the aDNA sequence from Neanderthal Vi-80 fossil with modern human X and Y chromosome sequence, and they found a similarity in 2.18 and 1.62 bases per 10,000 respectively, suggesting Vi-80 sample was from a male individual.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Other similar studies include finding of a mutation associated with dwarfism in *Arabidopsis* in ancient Nubian cotton, and investigation on the bitter taste perception locus in Neanderthals.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Modern humans are thought to have evolved in Africa at least 200 kya (thousand years ago), with some evidence suggesting a date of over 300 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Examination of mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA), Y-chromosome DNA, and X-chromosome DNA indicate that the earliest population to leave Africa consisted of approximately 1500 males and females.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] It has been suggested by various studies that populations were geographically "structured" to some degree prior to the expansion out of Africa; this is suggested by the antiquity of shared mtDNA lineages.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] One study of 121 populations from various places throughout the continent found 14 genetic and linguistic "clusters", suggesting an ancient geographic structure to African populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Genetic analysis has supported archaeological hypotheses of a large-scale migrations of Bantu speakers into Southern Africa approximately 5 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Microsatellite DNA, single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), and insertion/deletion polymorphisms (INDELS) have shown that Nilo-Saharan speaking populations originate from Sudan.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Furthermore, there is genetic evidence that Chad-speaking descendants of Nilo-Saharan speakers migrated from Sudan to Lake Chad about 8 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Genetic evidence has also indicated that non-African populations made significant contributions to the African gene pool.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] For example, the Saharan African Beja people have high levels of Middle-Eastern as well as East African Cushitic DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Analysis of mtDNA shows that modern humans occupied Eurasia in a single migratory event between 60 and 70 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Genetic evidence shows that occupation of the Near East and Europe happened no earlier than 50 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Studying haplogroup U has shown separate dispersals from the Near East both into Europe and into North Africa.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Much of the work done in archaeogenetics focuses on the Neolithic transition in Europe.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Cavalli-Sforza's analysis of genetic-geographic patterns led him to conclude that there was a massive influx of Near Eastern populations into Europe at the start of the Neolithic.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] This view led him "to strongly emphasize the expanding early farmers at the expense of the indigenous Mesolithic foraging populations." mtDNA analysis in the 1990s, however, contradicted this view.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Richards estimated that 10‚Äì22% of extant European mtDNA's had come from Near Eastern populations during the Neolithic.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Most mtDNA's were "already established" among existing Mesolithic and Paleolithic groups.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Most "control-region lineages" of modern European mtDNA are traced to a founder event of reoccupying northern Europe towards the end of the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM).
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] One study of extant European mtDNA's suggest this reoccupation occurred after the end of the LGM, although another suggests it occurred before.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Analysis of haplogroups V, H, and U5 support a "pioneer colonization" model of European occupation, with incorporation of foraging populations into arriving Neolithic populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Furthermore, analysis of ancient DNA, not just extant DNA, is shedding light on some issues.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] For instance, comparison of Neolithic and mesolithic DNA has indicated that the development of dairying preceded widespread lactose tolerance.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] South Asia has served as the major early corridor for geographical dispersal of modern humans from out-of-Africa.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Based on studies of mtDNA line M, some have suggested that the first occupants of India were Austro-Asiatic speakers who entered about 45‚Äì60 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The Indian gene pool has contributions from earliest settlers, as well as West Asian and Central Asian populations from migrations no earlier than 8 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The lack of variation in mtDNA lineages compared to the Y-chromosome lineages indicate that primarily males partook in these migrations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The discovery of two subbranches U2i and U2e of the U mtDNA lineage, which arose in Central Asia has "modulated" views of a large migration from Central Asia into India, as the two branches diverged 50 kya.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Furthermore, U2e is found in large percentages in Europe but not India, and vice versa for U2i, implying U2i is native to India.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Analysis of mtDNA and NRY (non-recombining region of Y chromosome) sequences have indicated that the first major dispersal out of Africa went through Arabia and the Indian coast 50‚Äì100 kya, and a second major dispersal occurred 15‚Äì50 kya north of the Himalayas.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Much work has been done to discover the extent of north-to-south and south-to-north migrations within Eastern Asia.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Comparing the genetic diversity of northeastern groups with southeastern groups has allowed archaeologists to conclude many of the northeast Asian groups came from the southeast.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The Pan-Asian SNP (single nucleotide polymorphism) study found "a strong and highly significant correlation between haplotype diversity and latitude," which, when coupled with demographic analysis, supports the case for a primarily south-to-north occupation of East Asia.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Archaeogenetics has also been used to study hunter-gatherer populations in the region, such as the Ainu from Japan and Negrito groups in the Philippines.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] A possible explanation of this is a recent admixture of some Negrito groups with their local populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Archaeogenetics has been used to better understand the populating of the Americas from Asia.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Native American mtDNA haplogroups have been estimated to be between 15 and 20 kya, although there is some variation in these estimates.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Genetic data has been used to propose various theories regarding how the Americas were colonized.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Although the most widely held theory suggests "three waves" of migration after the LGM through the Bering Strait, genetic data have given rise to alternative hypotheses.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] For example, one hypothesis proposes a migration from Siberia to South America 20‚Äì15 kya and a second migration that occurred after glacial recession.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Y-chromosome data has led some to hold that there was a single migration starting from the Altai Mountains of Siberia between 17.2 and 10.1 kya, after the LGM.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Finally, archaeogenetics has been used to study the occupation of Australia and New Guinea.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The Indigenous people of Australia and New Guinea are phenotypically very similar, but mtDNA has shown that this is due to convergence from living in similar conditions.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Non-coding regions of mt-DNA have shown "no similarities" between the aboriginal populations of Australia and New Guinea.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Furthermore, no major NRY lineages are shared between the two populations.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The high frequency of a single NRY lineage unique to Australia coupled with "low diversity of lineage-associated Y-chromosomal short tandem repeat (Y-STR) haplotypes" provide evidence for a "recent founder or bottleneck" event in Australia.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] But there is relatively large variation in mtDNA, which would imply that the bottleneck effect impacted males primarily.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Together, NRY and mtDNA studies show that the splitting event between the two groups was over 50 kya, casting doubt on recent common ancestry between the two.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Recent studies have noted many ethical and interpretational dilemmas linked to the use of ancient DNA in archaeological science.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The use of DNA in interpretations of rigid identities like those of sex or gender supports biological determinism in science.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Moreover, there are many ethical questions linked to research in ancient DNA if this research involves human remains.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] For example, Christopher Heaney (2023) in ‚ÄúCuring Incas,‚Äù in the context of Empires of the Dead, illustrates that many current descendant cultures view mummified ancestors not only as biological samples in science research but rather live beings in action.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] For this reason, many archaeologists consider that researchers should do research in terms of ancient DNA in collaboration and support of living descendants if research aims are compatible with values of the living society linked historically with the investigated DNA samples.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Archaeogenetics has been used to understand the development of domestication of plants and animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The combination of genetics and archeological findings have been used to trace the earliest signs of plant domestication around the world.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] However, since the nuclear, mitochondrial, and chloroplast genomes used to trace domestication's moment of origin have evolved at different rates, its use to trace genealogy have been somewhat problematic.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Nuclear DNA in specific is used over mitochondrial and chloroplast DNA because of its faster mutation rate as well as its intraspecific variation due to a higher consistency of polymorphism genetic markers.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Through the study of archaeogenetics in plant domestication, signs of the first global economy can also be uncovered.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The geographical distribution of new crops highly selected in one region found in another where it would have not originally been introduced serve as evidence of a trading network for the production and consumption of readily available resources.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Archaeogenetics has been used to study the domestication of animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] By analyzing genetic diversity in domesticated animal populations researchers can search for genetic markers in DNA to give valuable insight about possible traits of progenitor species.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] These traits are then used to help distinguish archaeological remains between wild and domesticated specimens.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The genetic studies can also lead to the identification of ancestors for domesticated animals.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] The information gained from genetics studies on current populations helps guide the Archaeologist's search for documenting these ancestors.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Archaeogenetics has been used to trace the domestication of pigs throughout the old world.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] These studies also reveal evidence about the details of early farmers.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Methods of Archaeogenetics have also been used to further understand the development of domestication of dogs.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Genetic studies have shown that all dogs are descendants from the gray wolf, however, it is currently unknown when, where, and how many times dogs were domesticated.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Some genetic studies have indicated multiple domestications while others have not.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Archaeological findings help better understand this complicated past by providing solid evidence about the progression of the domestication of dogs.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] As early humans domesticated dogs the archaeological remains of buried dogs became increasingly more abundant.
[src:molecular-genetics/archaeogenetics] Not only does this provide more opportunities for archaeologists to study the remains, it also provides clues about early human culture.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] The **Atlas of Genetics and Cytogenetics in Oncology and Haematology**, created in 1997 by Jean-Loup Huret (with bioinformatics by Philippe Dessen) is a collection of resources on genes, chromosomes anomalies, leukemias, solid tumours, and cancer-prone diseases.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] The project is accessible through Internet and is made of encyclopedic-style files, as well as traditional overviews, links towards websites and databases devoted to cancer and/or genetics, case reports in haematology.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] It also encompasses teaching items in various languages.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] This gives a wider and more global view of cancer genetics, while these data are usually dispersed.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] It includes a large iconography of about 35,000 images.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] Dan van Dyke said "This is one stop shopping that unifies cancer genetics information", and Lidia Larizza said that the Atlas was an "interdisciplinary resource".
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] The Atlas is part of the genome project and participates in research on cancer epidemiology.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] The Atlas is accessed by: 1- researchers in cytogenetics, molecular biology, cell biology; 2- clinicians, haematologists, cytogeneticists, pathologists, from the university hospitals, indeed, but also from general hospitals where the Atlas is one of the rare free resources.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] Junior doctors in haematology or oncology, are also most receptive to the Atlas that they see as a training and educational tool; 3-Students in medicine and life sciences.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] In 2017, it contains review articles on 1,500 genes, 700 papers on leukemias, 220 on solid tumors, and 110 on hereditary disease with a cancer-prone condition and 110 "Deep Insights" on related subjects, 40,000 internal links and 730,000 external links.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] More than 3,300 authors have/are contributing (1 130 North-American, 400 French, 300 Italian, 200 Japanese, 180 Spanish, 170 German, 160 English, 140 Chinese, etc...) .
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] It includes an iconography of about 35,000 images.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] In 2018, Jes√∫s Mar√≠a Hern√°ndez Rivas (Salamanca, Spain) and Paola Dal Cin (Boston, Massachusetts) joined Jean-Loup Huret as Co-Editors in Chief, and in April 2021 Alessandro Beghini (Milano, Italy) and Jo√£o Agostinho Machado-Neto (S√£o Paulo, Brazil) replace Jean-Loup Huret.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] "After 25 years building the Atlas day after day, Jean-Loup Huret and Philippe Dessen will take a little rest", as is said on the web site.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] The Atlas is also published as a scientific journal by CNRS, and is referenced by Scopus et Embase.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] The Atlas is financially supported by scientific societies, charities and individual donations.
[src:molecular-genetics/atlas-of-genetics-and-cytogenetics-in-oncology-and-haematology] More data is available from the site of the association in charge of the Atlas.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The field of study is based on the merging of several sub-fields in biology: classical Mendelian inheritance, cellular biology, molecular biology, biochemistry, and biotechnology.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] It integrates these disciplines to explore things like genetic inheritance, gene regulation and expression, and the molecular mechanism behind various life processes.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] A key goal of molecular genetics is to identify and study genetic mutations.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Researchers search for mutations in a gene or induce mutations in a gene to link a gene sequence to a specific phenotype.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Therefore molecular genetics is a powerful methodology for linking mutations to genetic conditions that may aid the search for treatments of various genetics diseases.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The discovery of DNA as the blueprint for life and breakthroughs in molecular genetics research came from the combined works of many scientists.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] He determined it was composed of hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen and phosphorus.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Biochemist Albrecht Kossel identified nuclein as a nucleic acid and provided its name deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA).
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] He continued to build on that by isolating the basic building blocks of DNA and RNA; made up of the nucleotides: adenine, guanine, thymine, cytosine, and uracil.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] His work on nucleotides earned him a Nobel Prize in Physiology.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] In the mid 19th century, anatomist Walther Flemming discovered what we now know as chromosomes and the separation process they undergo through mitosis.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] His work along with Theodor Boveri first came up with the chromosomal theory of inheritance, which helped explain some of the patterns Mendel had observed much earlier.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] For molecular genetics to develop as a discipline, several scientific discoveries were necessary.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The discovery of DNA as a means to transfer the genetic code of life from one cell to another and between generations was essential for identifying the molecule responsible for heredity.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Molecular genetics arose initially from studies involving genetic transformation in bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] In 1944 Avery, McLeod and McCarthy isolated DNA from a virulent strain of *S. pneumoniae*, and using just this DNA were able to convert a harmless strain to virulence.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] They called the uptake, incorporation and expression of DNA by bacteria "transformation".
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] This finding suggested that DNA is the genetic material of bacteria.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Bacterial transformation is often induced by conditions of stress, and the function of transformation appears to be repair of genomic damage.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] In 1950, Erwin Chargaff derived rules that offered evidence of DNA being the genetic material of life.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] In 1953 Francis Crick and James Watson, building upon the X-ray crystallography work done by Rosalind Franklin and Maurice Wilkins, were able to derive the 3-D double helix structure of DNA.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The phage group was an informal network of biologists centered on Max Delbr√ºck that contributed substantially to molecular genetics and the origins of molecular biology during the period from about 1945 to 1970.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The phage group took its name from bacteriophages, the bacteria-infecting viruses that the group used as experimental model organisms.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Studies by molecular geneticists affiliated with this group contributed to understanding how gene-encoded proteins function in DNA replication, DNA repair and DNA recombination, and on how viruses are assembled from protein and nucleic acid components (molecular morphogenesis).
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Furthermore, the role of chain terminating codons was elucidated.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] One noteworthy study was performed by Sydney Brenner and collaborators using "amber" mutants defective in the gene encoding the major head protein of bacteriophage T4.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] This study demonstrated the co-linearity of the gene with its encoded polypeptide, thus providing strong evidence for the "sequence hypothesis" that the amino acid sequence of a protein is specified by the nucleotide sequence of the gene determining the protein.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The isolation of a restriction endonuclease in *E. coli* by Arber and Linn in 1969 opened the field of genetic engineering.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Restriction enzymes were used to linearize DNA for separation by electrophoresis and Southern blotting allowed for the identification of specific DNA segments via hybridization probes.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] In 1971, Berg utilized restriction enzymes to create the first recombinant DNA molecule and first recombinant DNA plasmid.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] In 1972, Cohen and Boyer created the first recombinant DNA organism by inserting recombinant DNA plasmids into *E. coli*, now known as bacterial transformation, and paved the way for molecular cloning.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The development of DNA sequencing techniques in the late 1970s, first by Maxam and Gilbert, and then by Frederick Sanger, was pivotal to molecular genetic research and enabled scientists to begin conducting genetic screens to relate genotypic sequences to phenotypes.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) using Taq polymerase, invented by Mullis in 1985, enabled scientists to create millions of copies of a specific DNA sequence that could be used for transformation or manipulated using agarose gel separation.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] A decade later, the first whole genome was sequenced (*Haemophilus influenzae*), followed by the eventual sequencing of the human genome via the Human Genome Project in 2001.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The culmination of all of those discoveries was a new field called genomics that links the molecular structure of a gene to the protein or RNA encoded by that segment of DNA and the functional expression of that protein within an organism.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Today, through the application of molecular genetic techniques, genomics is being studied in many model organisms and data is being collected in computer databases like NCBI and Ensembl.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The computer analysis and comparison of genes within and between different species is called bioinformatics, and links genetic mutations on an evolutionary scale.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The central dogma plays a key role in the study of molecular genetics.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The central dogma states that DNA replicates itself, DNA is transcribed into RNA, and RNA is translated into proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Along with the central dogma, the genetic code is used in understanding how RNA is translated into proteins.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Replication of DNA and transcription from DNA to mRNA occurs in the nucleus while translation from RNA to proteins occurs in the ribosome.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The genetic code is made of four interchangeable parts of DNA molecules, called "bases": adenine, cytosine, thymine (uracil in RNA), and guanine and is redundant, meaning multiple combinations of these base pairs (which are read in triplicate) produce the same amino acid.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Proteomics and genomics are fields in biology that come out of the study of molecular genetics and the central dogma.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] An organism's genome is made up by its entire set of DNA and is responsible for its genetic traits, function and development.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The composition of DNA itself is an essential component to the field of molecular genetics; it is the basis of how DNA is able to store genetic information, pass it on, and be in a format that can be read and translated.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] DNA is a double stranded molecule, with each strand oriented in an antiparallel fashion.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Nucleotides are the building blocks of DNA, each composed of a sugar molecule, a phosphate group and one of four nitrogenous bases: adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] A single strand of DNA is held together by covalent bonds, while the two antiparallel strands are held together by hydrogen bonds between the nucleotide bases.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Adenine binds with thymine and cytosine binds with guanine.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] It is these four base sequences that form the genetic code for all biological life and contains the information for all the proteins the organism will be able to synthesize.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Its unique structure allows DNA to store and pass on biological information across generations during cell division.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] At cell division, cells must be able to copy its genome and pass it on to daughter cells.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] This is possible due to the double-stranded structure of DNA because one strand is complementary to its partner strand, and therefore each of these strands can act as a template strand for the formation of a new complementary strand.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] This is why the process of DNA replication is known as a semiconservative process.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Forward genetics is a molecular genetics technique used to identify genes or genetic mutations that produce a certain phenotype.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] In a genetic screen, random mutations are generated with mutagens (chemicals or radiation) or transposons and individuals are screened for the specific phenotype.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Often, a secondary assay in the form of a selection may follow mutagenesis where the desired phenotype is difficult to observe, for example in bacteria or cell cultures.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The cells may be transformed using a gene for antibiotic resistance or a fluorescent reporter so that the mutants with the desired phenotype are selected from the non-mutants.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Mutants exhibiting the phenotype of interest are isolated and a complementation test may be performed to determine if the phenotype results from more than one gene.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The mutant genes are then characterized as dominant (resulting in a gain of function), recessive (showing a loss of function), or epistatic (the mutant gene masks the phenotype of another gene).
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Finally, the location and specific nature of the mutation is mapped via sequencing.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Forward genetics is an unbiased approach and often leads to many unanticipated discoveries, but may be costly and time consuming.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Model organisms like the nematode worm *Caenorhabditis elegans*, the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster*, and the zebrafish *Danio rerio* have been used successfully to study phenotypes resulting from gene mutations.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Reverse genetics is the term for molecular genetics techniques used to determine the phenotype resulting from an intentional mutation in a gene of interest.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The phenotype is used to deduce the function of the un-mutated version of the gene.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Mutations may be random or intentional changes to the gene of interest.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Mutations may be a missense mutation caused by nucleotide substitution, a nucleotide addition or deletion to induce a frameshift mutation, or a complete addition/deletion of a gene or gene segment.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] The deletion of a particular gene creates a gene knockout where the gene is not expressed and a loss of function results (e.g. knockout mice).
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Missense mutations may cause total loss of function or result in partial loss of function, known as a knockdown.
[src:molecular-genetics/molecular-genetics] Knockdown may also be achieved by RNA interference (RNAi).
